<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Skinheads Face Murder Charge in B.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Five white supremacits have been
charged with beating a Sikh caretaker to death in the Canadian
province of British Columbia (B.C.), reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
All of the five, who aged from 17 to 25 years old and had
shaved heads, belong to a group known as White Power, which is
aligned with other white supremacist groups like Aryan Nations,
police said.
</P>
<P>
They were charged in provincial court with second-degree murder
in the January attack, in which the 65-year-old Sikh was
bludgeoned to death in the parking lot of a Sikh temple in the
Vancouver suburb of Surrey.
</P>
<P>
The killing might have been motivated by racial hatred, alleged
the police who are involved in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
The revelations of the murder came as a shock to some people in
Canada's west coast province.
</P>
<P>
"People knew racism was out there, but this is very
frightening," Rattan Mall, editor of a major Indo-Canadian
newspaper in Vancouver, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The slaying was "the tip of the iceberg" of hate crimes and
British Columbia has become a haven for those who commit such
crimes, noted anti-racist Allan Dutton.
</P>
<P>
Racists are moving to B.C. because the province has never
launched a prosecution under the section of the Criminal Code of
Canada dealing with hate propaganda or advocating genocide, Dutton
added.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that about 200 British Columbians are involved in
white, racist groups and an additional 2,000 are directly
connected to these organizations.
</P>
<P>
Dutton called for tougher laws to deal with race hatred, such
as making possession of hate literature a crime.
</P>
<P>
According to Peter Beaudin, executive director of the B.C.
Human Rights Coalition, there has been "a rising climate of
intolerance for the last 18 months in B.C.."
</P>
<P>
A decade of heavy immigration and a deepening economic downturn
now has contributed to increased anger and backlash in the
Vancouver region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
