<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25th Victim of Human BSE Dies in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Clare Tomkins, a 24-year-old
vegetarian, has become the 25th victim of the human version of BSE
and died in Britain Wednesday, a national newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Tomkins, who was from East Peckham, Kent,
and had been a vegetarian since 1985, fell ill in the Autumn of
1996.
</P>
<P>
After undergoing months of tests and treatment at several
hospitals, she was finally diagnosed as suffering from the new
variant CJD, which was linked two years ago to BSE in cattle, or
mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
During her illness, she lost weight and degenerated into a
tormented patient, racked by involuntary movements, unable to walk
unaided. Before her death, she was bed-bound, needing
round-the-clock nursing.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that her case may show that how long the
incubation period for the disease can be since she ate
beefburgers, hot dogs and other meat before she became a
vegetarian.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
