<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Care Ills Threaten Canada: Pollster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A national health-care crisis
instead of Quebec separation is the most difficult problem Canada
will face over the next decade, according to pollster Angus Reid.
</P>
<P>
"Everything I look at tells me Canada is likely to survive 10
years from now. It is highly unlikely we are going to have a
separate Quebec," Reid was quoted as saying by reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
What could really tear Canada apart in the new millennium is
the gradual erosion of something as fundamental as public health
care, said Reid, chief executive of the Angus Reid Group.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Canadians are most proud of their health-care
system. But an ever-growing number of people are getting more
about the health of the system, which is rapidly going downhill.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in a decade, health care has emerged as the
number one priority for Canadians.
</P>
<P>
"It's very likely we could find ourselves winning the battle
for Quebec but losing a broader war for the country, the battle
for our souls," he warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
