<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approves Adoption of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The lower house of the German
parliament, the Bundestag, Thursday gave overwhelming approval to
the country's adoption of the single European currency euro from
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The decision was approved by a vote of 575 to 35, with five
abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Most parliamentary members of German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
ruling coalition as well as the opposition Social Democratic Party
(SPD) and the Greens voted for the decision, while the Party of
Democratic Socialism (PDS) voted against and called for a
long-term delay in the euro launch.
</P>
<P>
Technically, Germany's adoption of the euro has still to get a
final approval from the upper house of the parliament, the
Bundesrat, which is due to vote on the issue on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Given the broad support from almost all the 16 state
governments whose representatives form the Bundesrat, that
approval is believed to be virtually certain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
