<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five IRA Prisoners to Be Transferred to Irish Jails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The British government agreed on
Thursday to transfer five IRA members serving sentences for murder
to prisons in the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw had agreed to the transfer, which
will be made shortly, under a Council of Europe convention on the
transfer of prisoners to their home countries, the Prison Service
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The service said the move was not directly related to the
Northern Irish peace deal, which could set free in the next two
years all jailed prisoners belonging to different political
parties in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Four of the prisoners were members of the so-called Balcombe
Street terrorist gang, who held a middle-aged couple hostage in
their central London home for six days in 1975 before they were
arrested. They are serving life sentences for two murders and
several bomb and gun attacks on the British mainland.
</P>
<P>
The fifth prisoner to be transferred is Paul Magee, who was
convicted of the murder of part-time policeman Glenn Goodman in
Yorkshire, northern England, in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
