<HEADLINE> Norway Launches Risk Capital Fund in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Norwegian government has
through its embassy in Harare launched a risk capital fund to
benefit joint ventures between Norwegian companies and those in
five southern African countries, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian Risk Capital Fund for Developing Countries
(NORFUND), launched by chairman Arve Johnsen on Thursday in
Zimbabwe's second largest city of Bulawayo, was allocated 30
million U.S. Dollars for this year.
</P>
<P>
It would benefit companies in Angola, Mozambique, South
Africa, Tanzania and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said Zimbabwe's share would depend on interest
shown by both Norwegian and Zimbabwean companies in joint
investment.
</P>
<P>
NORFUND would provide capital at an ownership share of between
35 percent and 49 percent of any business.
</P>
<P>
It would also privide loans, facilitate contact with
international financing bodies and act as a resource centre and
advisory board for beneficiaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
