<HEADLINE> Mkapa Denounces Detractors of Zimbabwean Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa Thursday urged Zimbabweans to guard against
enemies of the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic
Front (ZANU-PF) who despise their own independence.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing a ZANU-PF rally at Manama Business Center in
Mhondoro, southwest of Harare, after touring a multi-million
Dollar irrigation scheme in the area, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said most whites were against black majority rule during
Zimbabwe's protracted liberation war, and would try to manipulate
other black people to destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
"Don't be misled by them," he said, adding "They pretend to
offer systems and different models of government they think you
should establish."
</P>
<P>
"These models are inconsis;27t with what we fought for. Reject
their campaigns of slander and stand firm by your government," he
urged.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president praised Zimbabwe's land resettlement
program, saying it would ensure millions of the deprived to
improve their livelihood and restore their lost dignity.
</P>
<P>
He assured the support from Tanzania's ruling Chama Chama
Pinduzi party to Zimbabwe for the program.
</P>
<P>
According to Mkapa, the current visit will accord him a chance
to promote investment and trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe urged ZANU-PF members to
guard against exploitation by people working in the interests of
the enemy.
</P>
<P>
By June this year the majority of Zimbabweans would have
realised the practical benefits of government's efforts in trying
to resolve racial imbalances brought about by the colonial
governments, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This situation cannot be allowed to continue where we have
the greater part of our population living congested in the
communal areas," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is on a four-day official visit to Zimbabwe, is
scheduled to open the Zimbabwe International Trade Fair on
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
