<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Company to Advise Jordan on Privatizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's investment bank, EFG
Hermes, Thursday signed an agreement with the Jordanian
government to supervise the sale of 33 percent of the state's
shares in Jordan Cement Factories.
</P>
<P>
By the partial sale of the state's 49.5 percent ownership of
the profit-making private company's total shares, the government
expects to attract foreign capitals to help the company develop
its production capacity and increase its profits, Jordan's
official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The private company recorded 11.9 million Jordanian dinars
(about 16.8 million U.S. dollars) in net profits in 1997, but the
results were far from the government's expectations, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The sale is in line with the government's privatization policy
aimed at strengthening the national economy through giving a
larger role to the private sector and attracting foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Jordan Cement Factories is the second Jordanian company, where
the government's shares are to be sold to the private sector or
foreign investors under the kingdom's privatization plans. The
first is the Jordan Telecommunications Company.
</P>
<P>
Still on the privatization agenda are companies in
transportation, water and railway sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
