<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Loses 5 Billion US Dollars Each Year Due </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Fraud and error are costing the
European Union (EU) three billion pounds (about five billion U.S.
dollars) every year, according to a government watchdog report.
</P>
<P>
A report from the National Audit Office, published Thursday,
said that wastage makes up five percent of the EU's 60 billion
pounds (about 100 billion dollars) annual budget.
</P>
<P>
Among the errors cited in the report were 46,000 calves
slaughtered under a scheme to restrict veal supplies without
checks on whether the meat was properly disposed of.
</P>
<P>
John Bourn, head of National Audit Office, said that the level
of fraud identified by the European Court of Auditors "is a matter
for serious concern."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the implementation of a range of schemes
operated under the EU Common Agriculture Policy, including
premiums for the slaughter of cattle, has resulted in farmers
receiving more as well as less than their entitlement.
</P>
<P>
The report also expressed concern over the level of "errors"
found in payments from structural funds provided for regional
projects and called on the EU to produce clearer and simplified
budget statements with more accessible financial information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
