<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Denies Reports on Four-Party Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides said Thursday that U.S. State Department Special
Coordinator for Cyprus Thomas Miller has not proposed a
four-party meeting to reach a solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on recent Turkish reports that Miller
proposed to both Nicosia and Ankara a four-party meeting,
Clerides told reporters that "no such thing was put forward to
our side."
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities in Cyprus along with Greece and Turkey would be
invited to attend a meeting in an effort to reach a solution to
the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The reports were also dismissed Tuesday by Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides, who stressed that the Cypriot government is
aimed at the resumption of negotiations to settle the Cyprus
problem as early as possible, under U.N. aegis and based on the
international body's resolutions on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Miller was in Cyprus on Monday and met with both Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash before the forthcoming visit
here by U.S. presidential emissary Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides confirmed here
Thursday that Holbrooke will arrive here on May 1.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that the Cypriot government has not been
informed of a possible visit to Cyprus by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkey landed its troops and took over
the northern third of the island following a failed pro-Athens
coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
