<HEADLINE> Palestinian State to Be Established in 1999: PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
said Thursday that an independent Palestinian state will be
established in 1999, Jerusalem Media and Communication Center
(JMCC), a Palestinian press service, reported.
</P>
<P>
"Without this, the region will not see peace or stability,"
Tayeb Rahim, Secretary General to Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat, told graduating officers from a
personal security course.
</P>
<P>
Rahim added that "The Palestinian side is affirming the
establishment of a Palestinian state on all Palestinian lands with
respect to all international documents and will defeat all who
would stand in the way of our dream."
</P>
<P>
In response to the Israeli threat to enter Palestinian areas in
case of such a declaration, Rahim said that "if they enter, they
will not leave alive."
</P>
<P>
Arafat announced on several occasions that he will announce
the establishment of an independent Palestinian state in May of
1999 no matter the peace process has been moved forward or not.
</P>
<P>
He said on April 18 again that this announcement is in
accordance with the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu also said several
times that Israel will annex the PNA territories if the
declaration is announced.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian negotiations have been stalled for over
a year due to Israel's construction of Jewish settlement in Har
Homa near Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
So far, no substantial progress has been achieved in this
regard despite the efforts made by parties concerned for reviving
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
As arranged by the U.S. and Britain, Arafat and Netanyahu will
travel to London in early May to hold talks there separately with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called a meeting of PNA ministers and the Executive
Committee of the Palestine Liberation Organization Thursday
evening in Gaza to discuss the peace process and the issues for
the upcoming London meetings.
</P>
<P>
He will fly to Bonn on Friday to discuss all these issues with
German leaders, asking them to help push the process back on
track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
