<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Community Urged to Protect Ocean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) Thursday called on individuals, communities,
organizations and governments to take actions in protection of
ocean resources for future generations.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing held here Thursday, Paul Akiwumi, Program
Officer of UNEP's Water Branch, said that the United Nations
General Assembly had declared 1998 as the International Year of
the Ocean (IYO).
</P>
<P>
During the year, he said, UNEP planned to undertake various
activities to raise people's awareness on the importance of
oceans and seas to the everyday life and the necessity of
protecting this valuable source of life.
</P>
<P>
According to a background material distributed at the press
briefing, the capacity of oceans is huge in terms of heat
transfer, recycling greenhouse gases, absorbing pollutants and
sustaining marine life.
</P>
<P>
But, it noted, this capacity is limited especially in its
ability to absorb the effects of reckless development and
pollution.
</P>
<P>
There are visible signs of stress in oceans including
pollution, exhausted fishing stocks, disappearing coastlines,
rising sea level, increasing surface temperatures, more frequent
storms and melting ice caps.
</P>
<P>
For example, according to the U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO), 70 percent of fish stocks in oceans are
currently either fully exploited, overfished or in the process of
recovering from overfishing.
</P>
<P>
The International Year of the Ocean is designed to bring ocean
issues to the attention of decision-makers and the general
public, and the idea originally came from UNESCO's
Inter-governmental Oceanographic Commission (IOC).
</P>
<P>
The United Nations General Assembly formally adopted the
proposal in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to a program for IYO, the EXPO '98 will be held in
lisbon, capital of Portugal, from May 22 to September 30, with
the theme "the oceans, a heritage for the future".
</P>
<P>
During the year, ocean education is organized by IOC to
provide information on ways the oceans affect life on earth while
IOC prepares an overview of present scientific understanding of
the ocean.
</P>
<P>
The program said that a special UN series of postage stamps
will be issued in May 1998 with 20 member states of the IOC
issuing national postage stamps for the International Year of the
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
At least 30 conferences on ocean issues are planned for the
year all over the world, discussing themes including marine
pollution, coastal erosion, ocean circulation and problems of
mega-cities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than a dozen research and training cruises are
planned aboard vessels from Russia, Norway, China, India, Korea,
Indonesia, Canada, Malaysia and other countries.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has been charged with organizing the International
Year of the Ocean and UNEP is taking a leading role in the
development and implementation of the activity program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
