<HEADLINE> Peace Movement Welcomes EU's Intended Action on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Gush Shalom (Peace Movement of
Israel) Thursday welcomed the European Union's (EU) intention to
impose heavy duties on products from Jewish settlement in the West
Bank as an effort to oppose Israel's settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
"Gush Shalom regards the intended EU's move as a welcome
expression of its stated position regarding the peace process,"
the organization said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's edition of "Yediot Aharonot," Israel's leading
Hebrew newspaper, reported that the EU is preparing a list of
goods produced at Israeli settlements in the occupied territories
and presently exported to EU members, including agricultural
products, processed foods, wines, flowers and others.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, secret reports reaching the Israeli
Embassy in Brussels indicate that the Europeans are about to
impose customs duties on the products on this list.
</P>
<P>
Agreements between Israel and the EU give a partial or
complete exemption from customs duties to Israeli products of
these categories. But in international law, the occupied
territories are not part of Israel, and therefore the settlement
products would, upon publication of the list, be subjected to
heavy customs duties.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry said Thursday that the government is
making diplomatic efforts to block the EU move, which it regards
as a grave threat politically more than economically.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry also said EU's proposed move would also
violate the Oslo Accords, which give exemptions from customs
duties to products of the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
However, local experts pointed out, that line of argument of
the Israeli Foreign Ministry leads to the conclusion that, to be
eligible for customs exemptions, the settlement products must
register with the Palestinian Ministry of Trade and Industry, pay
Palestinian taxes and have their products stamped "made in
Palestine."
</P>
<P>
"It has long been clear that the Israeli settlements in the
occupied territories constitute the main obstacle on the way to
peace in our region," Gush Shalom's statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The existence of the settlements as armed enclaves which
constantly encroach on ever-more Palestinian lands, constantly
guarded by Israeli soldiers who often outnumbered the settlers
themselves, is totally incompatible with peace," it added.
</P>
<P>
"The intended move of the EU would bring this point home -- to
the settlers and the government which backs them -- and that is
the best contribution which Europe could make to the achievement
of peace," the statement concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: German Parliament Gives Green Light to Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The lower house of the German
parliament Thursday gave overwhelming support for the single
European currency euro, clearing a final hurdle for Germany to
adopt the common currency along with ten other European Union
states from January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious EU project was approved by the German Bundestag
by a vote of 575 to 35 with five abstentions.
</P>
<P>
"This is one of the most important decision in the European
integration process," said German Chancellor Helmut Kohl in his
speech to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"The euro opens great chances for new economic dynamic, for
lasting growth and secure jobs in the 21th century," he added.
</P>
<P>
Despite the broad support, the full-day parliamentary debate
also highlighted the dispute between Kohl's ruling coalition and
opposition parties about what should be done after the euro launch
and especially about social and employment policies.
</P>
<P>
While the government stressed the need for further fiscal
discipline to ensure a stable euro and called for fundamental
structural reforms to improve Germany's competitiveness,
opposition parties including Social Democrats (SPD) warned that
the euro could also create new divisions in Europe and its success
is still dependent on European-wide harmonization of taxation,
job-creation and social policies.
</P>
<P>
With Germany's next general elections just five months away,
both the SPD and the Greens also accused Kohl's government of
having blocked efforts to hold a referendum on the euro in the
country, which they said is part of reasons for the widespread
Euroscepticism among the German public.
</P>
<P>
Recent opinion polls show that between 50 to 70 percent of
Germans are still dismayed about abandoning their rock-hard German
mark in favor of the still untested euro.
</P>
<P>
Created exactly 50 years ago, the mark has been cherished by
German voters as the symbol for the country's economic miracle in
the post-war era and a safeguard against skyrocketing inflations
that robbed their savings early this century.
</P>
<P>
While expressing sympathy for the public sentiment, Kohl
stressed that due to the arduous economic convergence efforts made
by EU states as well as the so-called stability pact designed to
ensure future currency stability, he believed "the success story
of the Deutsche Mark will continue with the success of the euro".
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, German politicians on Thursday also held
back from challenging the euro membership of Italy and Belgium,
whose high public debt is seen as a major factor risking the
stability of the euro.
</P>
<P>
Public debt in both countries is currently over 120 percent of
gross domestic product, doubling the 60 percent ceiling set by the
EU Maastricht Treaty for euro members.
</P>
<P>
The final decision adopted by the Bundestag only required that
"further considerable efforts, especially with regard to debt
reduction, are still needed in order to guarantee an acceptable
fiscal fitness without additional transfers of financial
assistance within the EU".
</P>
<P>
Speaking for his Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS), which
emerged as the sole parliamentary group voting against the euro on
Thursday, PDS leader Gregor Gysi stressed that social justice had
been neglected in the European drive to launch the euro which is
expected to only benefit the large companies and employers.
</P>
<P>
With the approval at the Bundestag, Germany's adoption of the
euro now only needs a final endorsement on Friday from the upper
house of parliament, the Bundesrat, which represents the country's
16 federal states.
</P>
<P>
Although the eastern German Saxony state has threatened to cast
a negative vote, this is not expected to derail the project which
only needs an approval of a simple majority at the Bundesrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: Military Aid to Egypt May Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Cohen said on Thursday the annual 1.3 billion U.S. dollars of
U.S. military assistance to Egypt will continue and could grow in
the coming years.
</P>
<P>
He said in an interview with a Cairo T.V. program that
Washington is determined to consolidate the peace process to
strengthen security and stability in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Cohen ended a two-day visit to Egypt last Monday as part of a
tour of the region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is not interested in achieving a balance of power in
the region, "but strives at consolidating peace through forging
stronger relations" among Israel and two Arab countries of Egypt
and Jordan, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also disowned the claim of a complete U.S. support for
Israel at the expense of Arab interests, saying that the U.S. also
supports Egypt and Jordan in various fields and backs other Arab
countries as well.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. supports Egypt on a large scale, and the two
countries have joint programs in the field of active technology,
including program on frigates and F-16 aircraft," he said in the
interview.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official added that his country is helping Egypt
modernize its army through the introduction of the most
sophisticated defense systems.
</P>
<P>
Cohen told reporters in Cairo last Sunday that the
U.S.-Egyptian cooperation program in 1998 includes the
U.S. provision of 15 adventure vehicles with stinger missiles, two
frigates and torpedos, anti-ship missiles, and co-production of
tank-recovery vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Cairo has been receiving U.S. military and economic aid since
1979. But it offered recently to the Clinton administration to
reduce the annual economic aid it gets from Washington in return
for increased military aid.
</P>
<P>
Washington's allocations in 1998 for Egypt totaled 2.1 billion
dollars, including 800 million dollars in economic aid and 1.3
billion in military. The two countries have been held an annual
war game since Egypt signed a U.S.-brokered peace treaty with
Israel in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
