<HEADLINE> Strong Pound Is Damaging UK's Export: CBI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The strong pound is doing real
damage to Britain's exporters, said Colin Marshall, President of
the Confederation of British Industry (CBI) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a CBI gathering to an audience of British
manufacturers, Colin said that the strong pound is "having adverse
effects on the bottom line for many companies where foreign
currency earnings contribute to profits."
</P>
<P>
Before the end of March, the pound climbed to its strongest
level in nine years, increasing pressure on the UK exporters.
</P>
<P>
Sterling's strength has cut confidence among exporters to its
lowest for nearly seven years, according to Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, a
research institute. Only 47.5 percent of companies expected higher
exports over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Colin also recognized that there is a productivity gap between
the UK and its French and German competitors, but made clear that
could not be tackled over night.
</P>
<P>
He said: "It has been suggested that manufacturers have been
unduly vocal about sterling and have not been paying enough
attention to maintaining the productivity drive."
</P>
<P>
Colin supported Chancellor Golden Brown's call to business to
control wage costs and further improve productivity.
</P>
<P>
However, a report by the Foundation for Manufacturing and
Industry (FMI) warns that the UK is moving down the
competitiveness league in terms of labor costs.
</P>
<P>
The minimum wage could "further increase labor compensation
costs", said Jane Croot, FMI economist.  
</P>
</TEXT>
