<HEADLINE> Two Belgian Ministers to Resign for Paedophile Escape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian deputy prime
minister and justice minister sent in their resignation on
Thursday following the escape of alleged child rapist and killer
Marc Dutroux.
</P>
<P>
Resignations by Deputy Prime Minister and Interior Minister
Johan Vande Lanotte and Justice Minister Stefaan de Clerck were
sent to Belgian King Albert II.
</P>
<P>
But the king, who interrupted his vacation abroad to return to
the country after receiving the news of the escape, has not
accepted the resignation yet.
</P>
<P>
The intention to resign by the two ministers was announced by
Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene who said at the lower
house of the parliament that it was clear that such an incident
was hardly understandable and forgivable.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian police have recaptured the alleged child killer a
few hours after he ran away from a court at Neufchateau.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was caught in southeastern Belgium, close to the
borders with Luxembourg and France, police sources said.
</P>
<P>
The alleged child killer managed to run away from one police
guard in the court and started his run in a stolen car toward the
borders of Luxembourg and France.
</P>
<P>
Belgian police had to seal off the borders while the French
police did the same on their side of the border. Police in five
countries were mobilized to join the manhunt.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was accused of killing four of the six young girls he
had abducted in mid 1996 as a nation-wide child sex ring was
exposed and shocked the Belgian public.
</P>
<P>
The lower house of the Belgian Parliament adjoined its
afternoon session to press the cabinet for an explanation for the
runaway of the alleged child killer.
</P>
<P>
The senate also pressed for an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
There are usually two armed gendarmes on duty to guard such an
alleged criminal in court but there was only one police at present
when Dutroux was taken to the Neufchateau court for his first
hearing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Condemns U.N. Human Rights Resolution on Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Thursday condemned a
resolution of the United Nations Human Right Commission (UNHRC)
on Iran's human rights status, terming it as politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said the resolution on Iran
has nothing to do with the realities in the country, adding that
the human rights were misused by certain countries for political
ends.
</P>
<P>
The UNHRC passed the resolution on Iran in Geneva on Wednesday,
blaming the Iranian government for abusing human rights.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that the UNHRC has not even been taken into
account the report of the U.N. rapporteur Maurice Danby
Copithorne on the human rights situation in Iran and the
resolution was merely passed by the western states' pressure on
the members of the commission.
</P>
<P>
He added that the resolution has adopted a spirit of
confrontation with the Islamic law and values instead of
encouraging the value-oriented cultural exchange between the
civilizations.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating that Iran is cooperating with the UNHRC, he
stressed that human rights in Iran has religious foundation and it
would make its best to honor the human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
