<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
Tunis -- Tunisian pharmaceutical plants have been able to
supply 40 percent of the national medicine needs, up from 12
percent in 1989, according to statistics by the Tunisian Health
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The plants, numbering 20, currently produce 1,800 kinds of
medicines.
</P>
<P>
The statistics estimated the value of the medicines consumed by
the local market at 200 million U.S. dollars per year, of which 50
million dollars were by individuals.
</P>
<P>
Luxor (Egypt) -- Egypt, Syria, Lebanon and Kuwait have agreed
to start carrying out a plan on exchanging products made by
cooperatives in the four countries, and for granting these goods
marketing privileges.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Chairman of Egypt's Central Cooperative
Production Union, Mohammed Hassan El-Seba'ai, following a special
four-side meeting held during the Arab Cooperative Union
conference which concluded here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The plan was aimed at creating a strong impetus to the Egyptian
political leadership's trend to establish an Arab common market
and to set up an inter-Arab free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian and Greek governments signed here
Thursday letters under which Greece will offer Jordan 500,000
U.S. dollars of grants to help the kingdom curb poverty and
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The grants will be used by the Social Security Program which
is sponsored by the Jordanian government, Jordan's official news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that Greece provides financial
assistance to Jordan's development projects.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The volume of Jordan's exports reached about 1 billion
Jordanian dinars (1.5 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997 and the
exports covered 120 Arab and other foreign countries, Amman
Chamber of Industry President Khaldun Abu Hassan said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Industrial products, including potash, fertilizers,
pharmaceuticals, as well as chemical and plastic products, took 90
percent of the total exports in 1997, Jordan's official news
agency quoted Hassan as saying while meeting a visiting Italian
economic delegation.
</P>
<P>
Major importers of Jordanian commodities were Iraq, Saudi
Arabia, the Arab Gulf states and the Palestinian self-rule areas,
he added.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Six foreign banks from Canada, Turkey, the United Arab
Emirates, Pakistan, Germany and Switzerland have announced their
readiness to open branch offices in Iran's free trade zone of the
Qeshm island at the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
A law that allows foreign banks to operate in Iran's free
trade zones becomes operative this month, the Iranian official
news agency IRNA reported on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
