<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Budget Deficit Drops in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese budget deficit
moderately dropped in the first three months of this year,
preliminarily reflecting the progress the country has made in
its efforts to curb the ballooning deficit.
</P>
<P>
An official report issued by the Finance Ministry Thursday said
that the state collected 1,024 billion Lebanese pounds (about 673
million U.S. dollars) of revenues and spent 1,492 billion pounds
(about 980 million dollars) in first quarter of this year,
resulting in a deficit of 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures are well below the government's 42 percent deficit
target for 1998 and compare favorably with the 55 percent for
the same period of last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But economists said that it is too early to judge the
government's fiscal performance.
</P>
<P>
The ministry stressed in the report that it would continue to
take any necessary measures to curb huge spending on the one
hand, and increase revenues on the other, in order to gradually
reduce the country's increasing deficit in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The economy of Lebanon, which is undergoing a
multi-billion-dollar reconstruction drive to rebuild its
war-ravaged economy, deteriorated last year due to an unexpected
increased deficit of 59 percent, far over the 36 percent
budgetary forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
