<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan, U.S. Strengthen Cooperation on Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkmenistan and the United
States signed on Thursday an agreement on the feasibility study of
a trans-Caspian pipeline that will be granted 750,000 U.S. dollars
by the U.S. Trade and Development Agency.
</P>
<P>
The study will evaluate the construction of a new East-West
pipeline which would take gas across Turkmenistan under the
Caspian Sea, through Azerbaijan and Georgia and into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed at a White House ceremony attended by
U.S. Vice-President Al Gore and visiting Turkmenistani President
Saparmurat Niyazov.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov, who ended his three-day official visit to the United
States, had a luncheon with U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"The two presidents agreed on the importance of developing
Turkmenistan's energy resources, including a trans-Caspian transit
corridor to bring the significant oil and gas resources of that
region to market," White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also signed several other documents for
cooperation in energy, science and technology, agriculture,
and security relations.
</P>
<P>
"Given Turkmenistan's significant position in the region, and
given its historical associations with the government of Russia,
we have a keen interest in the role that they play with respect to
regional economic security," McCurry told a briefing at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
However, McCurry denied that the joint statement on security
provides security guarantee for Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a security guarantee, this is a joint statement on
security aspects of our bilateral relationship," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also expressed the U.S. concern over Turkmenistan's
cooperation with Iran.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
