<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis Dampens Canadian Growth: Thiessen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Canada Governor Gordon
Thiessen said Thursday that the Asian crisis will have a dampening
influence on Canadian economy this year.
</P>
<P>
"The effects on the Canadian economy of the problems in Asia
are likely to come mainly via our other major trading partners and
through the prices of some of our exports, especially primary
commodities," Thiessen told the Senate Banking Committee
</P>
<P>
"This effects will no doubt have a dampening influence on
economic activity in Canada this year."
</P>
<P>
British Columbia will be hardest hit since the province has a
heavy reliance on the primary commodity sector and on exports to
Asia, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the outlook for the Canadian economy is
"still positive", though Asian crisis has led to a scaling back of
earlier projections for world economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Stronger than expected economic performances in Canada's major
trading partners, particularly the United States, would help to
offset the Asian impact, he said.
</P>
<P>
And Canada has a much sounder economic foundation than in the
past thanks to low inflation, improved fiscal health and progress
made in private sector restructuring.
</P>
<P>
"This puts us in a better position to withstand shocks such as
those emanating from Asia," the governor noted.
</P>
<P>
"On balance, the Canadian economic outlook remains positive,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund projected economic growth of
3.2 percent in Canada this year. "This is generally in line with
our own projections," the governor said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
