<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seaweeds Flourish in Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Seaweeds farming in the
isles of Zanzibar has flourished and brought wealth to local
people in recent years, a researcher of marine science has said.
</P>
<P>
Exports of seaweeds grew to 4871.2 tons in 1996 from 932.5
tons in 1990, making the crop the third largest foreign exchange
earner in the isles after cloves and tourism, said Nariman
Jiddawi with the Zanzibar Institute of Marine Science.
</P>
<P>
Jiddawi, who was presenting a paper Thursday on the importance
of seaweeds farming to the livelihood security of the people of
Zanzibar at an international workshop, said seaweeds farming
initially started in two villages has expanded to 34 villages in
Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
The crop was dried and exported to the United States, Denmark
and France, she told 60 participants at the second international
training workshop on the zero emissions research initiatives in
Africa, which ended here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Seaweed is usually used as food and in the pharmaceutical
industries to manufacture drugs.
</P>
<P>
There are five species of seaweeds, but the common ones in
Zanzibar are: euchuma catonii, an indigenous species, and euchuma
spinosum which was introduced in the isles from the Philippines
during the early 1990s after the local variety failed to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
Seaweeds farming in the east coast of Zanzibar has become a
major economic activity particularly to women and children who
constitute about 90 percent of the labor force, she said.
</P>
<P>
Three major companies -- Zanea, Zascol and C-Weed are engaging
in the seaweeds business, she said. They purchase the crop at
100,000 Shillings (about 150 U.S. Dollars) per ton from farmers
and export them at 250 U.S. Dollars to 800 dollars per ton.
</P>
<P>
The exporters usually provide the farmers with the seedlings
and implements such as ropes on condition that they sell the
dried crop to them.
</P>
<P>
Jiddawi explained that on average a farmer earn between 25,000
to 70,000 Shillings from selling seaweeds. She also said there
are plans to start seaweeds farming in ponds as measures to
further expand the production.
</P>
<P>
The crop has created job opportunities and improved the
nutrition and welfare of the people of Zanzibar, she said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which has been organized by the Tanzania
Commission for Science and Technology and sponsored bhe United
Nations Development Program (UNDP), will be followed by a
field trip to Zanzibar to see the seaweeds farms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., S.Korea Reach Open Skies Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Untied States has reached
a liberal aviation accord with South Korea, U.S. Transportation
Secretary Rodney Stater said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The open skies pact would allow airlines of both countries to
operate air services between the two countries without
restriction, he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States started talks with South Korea on the liberal
aviation last year. The accord was reached after three rounds of
negotiations. And South Korea now becomes the largest open skies
partner of the United States in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The United States now has open skies agreements with 30
aviation partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
