<HEADLINE> Turkey to Hold Early Elections in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will hold early elections
in March, 1999 and will establish an election government this
October, state-run TRT television reported here Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Republican People's Party (CHP) Chairman
Deniz Baykal, who had a working lunch with Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz, as saying that he and Yilmaz had agreed to hold local and
parliamentary elections on the last Sunday of March, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The consensus between Baykal and Yilmaz, also leader of the
Motherland Party, ended weeks of tension and early election
debate between coalition partners and the CHP, with whose
external support the minority government is surviving.
</P>
<P>
The CHP has conditioned its support to the government on an
early election.
</P>
<P>
Baykal said he and the prime minister were in full agreement to
establish an election government headed by an independent deputy
to make sure that there wouldn't be an election economy in the
country from October to March.
</P>
<P>
A government headed by an independent deputy is a safeguard as
well against the possible use of state funds in favor of any party
during the campaign period, said the CHP leader.
</P>
<P>
Following the Yilmaz-Baykal meeting, the prime minister met
with Deputy Prime Minister and Left Democratic Party (DSP)
Chairman Bulent Ecevit to convey to him the results of his
meeting with Baykal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
