<HEADLINE> Technology Transfer on Agenda 21 Emphasized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Developed countries should
honor their commitment to transferring technology to their
developing counterparts to ensure the implementation of Agenda 21,
a Chinese delegate said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Taking the floor at the on-going session of the U.N. Commission
on Sustainable Development (CSD), deputy head of the Chinese
Delegation Zhang Kunmin said only the environmentally sound and
advanced technologies can efficiently help meet developing
countries' needs for poverty eradication and an improvement of
environment.
</P>
<P>
Besides giving priority to encouraging their public sector to
transfer environmentally sound technology to developing nations,
developed countries should stimulate private enterprises to do so,
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The CSD was set up in 1992 to track the progress in
implementing Agenda 21 adopted at the Rio Earth Summit. The
current CSD annual session runs from April 20 to May 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
