<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opponents of NATO Expansion Claim They're Gaining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Senators opposed to expanding
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) claimed they are
gaining more support but admitted that they are on a uphill and
would not be able to stop the move.
</P>
<P>
As the Senate is to debate on the measure to add Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic to the military alliance, both
sides were generally predicting Senate approval, which seems
likely to take place sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, one of nine
senators who denounced the legislation at the press conference,
said it was hard to persuade people expansion was bad because
"everybody likes NATO" and feels expanding it "must be positive."
</P>
<P>
They argue that the expansion will cost U.S. taxpayers untold
billions, needlessly alienate Moscow, force the United States into
dangerous military alliances and blur NATO's mandate.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator John Warner of Virginia asked, "What will it
do? What's its mission?". He added that the expansion could turn
NATO into "a mini-U.N."
</P>
<P>
A two-thirds majority vote is needed for ratifying the
alliance's plan.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member NATO extended invitations to Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic last July and completed accession negotiations
in December last year.
</P>
<P>
Key arguments against NATO expansion include the concern that
it will exacerbate tensions with Russia, result in substantial
costs and risks that the allies are unwilling to share and the
American people are unwilling to shoulder alone, and dilute the
mission, policy-making and military effectiveness of the alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
