<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ambassador Presses Congress to Pay U.N. Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States could save
100 million U.S. dollars a year in U.N. dues if Congress approves
payment of a major part of the arrears owed to the organization,
U.S. Ambassador Bill Richardson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a House appropriate subcommittee, he also warned
the United States could lose its vote in the United Nations by the
end of the year unless the debt issue is resolved.
</P>
<P>
He said the Clinton administration remains open to any
compromise that would separate U.N. funding from U.S. payments to
family-planning organizations.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said passage of the request for payment of most of
the 1.3 billion U.S. dollars it owes the organization by the end
of May would open the way for talks this summer on reducing the
annual U.S. contribution from 25 percent of the U.N. budget to 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
"Failure to pass the necessary legislation in time will cause
us to squander this unique opportunity and we will be unable to
reopen the scales of assessment (talks ) until the fall of 2000,"
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
The Senate approved a plan to pay more than 800 million U.S.
dollars in U.N. arrears, but it was derailed in the House of
Representatives when Clinton refused to accept amendments to
outlaw funds for abortion.
</P>
<P>
The full committee has approved 505 million U.S. dollars for
payment of U.S. arrears but Richardson said the administration
needed the 921 million U.S. dollars in its initial request.
</P>
<P>
"Our closest friends in the U.N. are warning us that we face a
decidedly uphill battle even with the full amount the
administration is requesting" to get the U.S assessment reduced,
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
Congress has held up payments of U.N. debts for years to demand
reduction in U.S. payments and streamlining in the world
organization.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said that U.N. reform has become unrelenting under
the leadership of Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who has cut
administrative costs by one-third, merged three departments into
one and eliminated nearly 1,000 positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
