<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Western Cape Leader Elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The future premier of South
Africa's Western Cape Province was elected Thursday night,
marking the first time that a colored person takes the top post
of the province.
</P>
<P>
The province's Safety MEC (Member of Executive Council) Gerald
Morkel was elected to succeed Hernus Kriel as Western Cape National
Party (NP) leader, and hence automatically the premier of the
province, where the NP holds the majority in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
Morkel, 57, would be sworn in on May 11 and he will hold the post
until next year's general election.
</P>
<P>
Morkel, the most senior provincial minister, as well as leader of
the provincial legislature and deputy premier, is expected to lead the
NP in the crucial battle of the coming election in Western Cape to
secure the last NP stronghold constituency.
</P>
<P>
The NP's Western Cape head council chose Morkel Thursday night in
preference to Health MEC Peter Marais, 54.
</P>
<P>
Morkel is widely seen as a suave, diplomatic personality, a man
more capable of uniting the party than Marais, who is often described
as "firebrand" and "unguided missile".
</P>
<P>
However, some doubted that Morkel, who is seen as lacking political
shrewdness.
</P>
<P>
The timing of Kriel's resignation, announced Monday, was
interpreted as making way for a colored new NP leader, a move to
secure colored votes for the NP which are critical in the coming
election.
</P>
<P>
Morkel, a stalwart of the former Labor Party in the erstwhile house
of representatives, joined the NP in 1991.  
</P>
</TEXT>
