<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees no Sufficient Grounds to Lift Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Thursday
dismissed any possibilities of lifting the seven-year sanctions as
Iraq has repeatedly demanded.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the Clinton
administration has "seen insufficient grounds" to lift the
sanctions and said Iraq must comply "with a whole host" of
requirements before the embargo is removed.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on Thursday sent a
letter to the president of the Security Council, claiming that
Iraq had fulfilled all the disarmament requirements of a key 1991
council resolution, and demanding to end the sanctions against his
country.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq demands that the Security Council implement paragraph 22
of resolution 687 immediately without any new restrictions or
conditions," Aziz said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
The paragraph in the resolution provides the easing of
sanctions, once all Iraq's nuclear, chemical, biological and
ballistic weapons have been scrapped and steps taken to ensure
they cannot be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
Aziz also accused U.N. chief weapons inspector Richard Butler
of spreading "fallacies and lies."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a report Butler submitted to the Security
Council last Friday, which said that there had been "virtually no
progress" made in verifying whether Iraq has destroyed banned
weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council will discuss the reports next week. And
State Department spokesman James Rubin expected no one in the
Security Council would advocate the lifting of the sanctions
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I can't imagine, based on the report that Chairman Butler
ahs provided, that any country in the Security Council would be
advocating a suspension of any part of the sanctions regime," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
