<HEADLINE> Iraqi Cabinet Slams UNSCOM Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi cabinet Thursday described
an UNSCOM's (U.N. Special Commission) report as an attempt to
block Iraq's effort for lifting the U.N.-imposed sanctions on it,
the Iraqi News Agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting chaired by President Saddam Hussein
discussed UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler's semi-annual report to
the U.N. Security Council, which said that there are still
obstacles standing in the way of arms inspection and that Iraq has
not fully cooperated with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990 can not be lifted unless the UNSCOM in charge of
eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction verifies that Iraq
is free of banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet said that Iraq's cooperation with the
U.N. inspectors is meant to offer an opportunity for the world
community to make a concerted effort to lift the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
But "Such attempts (like Butler's report) by the United States
were intended to perpetuate the sanctions to secure a streamline
implementation of its conspiratorial agenda against the world,
Arab nation and the Middle East," the INA quoted cabinet members
as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
