<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-23 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, N. Cyprus to Further Strengthen Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and northern Cyprus
declared here on Thursday that they would further enhance
cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
This came in a joint declaration issued at the end of the
official talks between Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash who arrived in Istanbul
Wednesday for a two-day official visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said that northern Cyprus would continue to
exist as an independent and sovereign state, adding that the
relations between Turkey and northern Cyprus in all fields would
be further deepened and strengthened.
</P>
<P>
It strongly criticized the European Union's (EU) decision to
start accession talks with Cyprus, terming the EU Luxembourg
summit, at which the decision was made, as an "historic mistake."
</P>
<P>
It said that "the military, economic and political integration
which Greece and Greek Cyprus are virtually accomplishing
obstructs the efforts for a solution on the island."
</P>
<P>
The declaration noted that any further talks between the two
sides in Cyprus could be held only on the basis of two
sovereign and equal states, adding that northern Cyprus is ready
to take part in any negotiations within this framework.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in the north in 1983, which is only recognized
by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Pursues Two Goals in China Trip: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will pursue two goals in her trip to China next
week: summit preparation and continuation of strategic dialogue, a
senior State Department official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Summit preparation is a key point in going," said the
official, who indicated the U.S. willingness to follow up the
issues identified for joint efforts when Chinese President Jiang
Zemin came to visit the U.S. last fall.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang and his U.S. counterpart, Bill Clinton, agreed
at their Washington summit in late October that the two countries
should establish a constructive strategic partnership for the 21st
century. President Clinton is scheduled to return a visit to China
by the end of June to have another summit meeting with Jiang in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"There are certain priorities. But first, across the board,
what we want to do is move along what was agreed to the last time
when President Jiang Zemin came to the U.S. and there it was
agreed that we would work on what was identified as nine `baskets'
of issues and try to achieve progress in all of them," said the
official.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "baskets" of issues mainly include human rights,
non-proliferation, trade and commerce, energy and environment. The
official said that priority will be given to the human rights
issue, non-proliferation and trade.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Albright will arrive in Beijing Wednesday
following her visit to Japan. China is the second leg of her
four-nation trip which will also take her to South Korea and
Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The official said that this is the first of four trips planned
by the secretary of state to Asia this year, showing importance
the U.S. attaches to the region.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state will continue "strategic dialogue" with
Chinese officials, the second goal of her trip as described by the
official.
</P>
<P>
"We sit down with China the way we do with other important
relationships and we talk about the world; not just about the
focus on the immediate bilateral problems," the official said.
</P>
<P>
"The idea is that two major powers should be talking to each
other about a whole range of foreign policy issues, and not just
having a relationship that focuses on the discrete problems," the
official added.
</P>
<P>
It is said that Albright will meet with Vice Premier Qian
Qichen, Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and some other Chinese
officials during her stay in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The official believed that the Sino-U.S. relationship is "on a
good trajectory," with progress being made on a large number of
areas including human rights and non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
However, the official said that there is a lot of work left
ahead of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
China's access to the World Trade Organization and the Taiwan
issue are among the problems which need more efforts to settle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
