<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Crime, Kids Greatest Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The interrelated issues of
crime, children's well-being and drug abuse lead a list of
national concerns revealed Thursday in the Healthy Kids Public
Opinion Survey by the Young Men's Christian Association (YMCA).
</P>
<P>
White House scandals rank low on a survey of the nation's
concerns, rated most important by only 2 percent of respondents.
</P>
<P>
Three-quarters of respondents said child care today has become
"a greater problem" for Americans than it was 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
As to what attributes are important to good child care, 98
percent agreed that selecting a safe and caring environment is
"very" or "somewhat" important, while 98 percent said the same
about programs that educate and develop social skills.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-seven percent consider instruction in the values of
caring, honesty, respect and responsibility to be "very" or
"somewhat" important.
</P>
<P>
Lynne Vaughan, national YMCA spokesperson, said, "When it comes
right down to it, it's not political scandals, government or taxes
that worry Americans. It's much closer to home. It's the safety
and nurturing of our children and the values that they're
learning."
</P>
<P>
A majority worry that quality child care may not be available
for themselves and their friends and family, or may be too costly
to fill the national demand. Only 69 percent of those questioned
said they have children.
</P>
<P>
The survey comprised 600 interviews with adults nationwide and
was conducted March 25-29. Margin of error is plus or minus 4
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
