<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar Thursday rose
against major European currencies for the second consecutive day
as traders sold the German mark and the Swiss franc to gain the
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The dollar slipped against the Japanese yen in lackluster
trading partly because investors are waiting for details of an
economic stimulus package the Japanese government will unveil
Friday.
 at 1.7983
marks, up from 1.7940 late Wednesday. It also was changing hands
at 130.18 yen, down from 130.28.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, investors decided to take profits, selling the
mark and the Swiss franc against the yen. That helped make the yen
stronger in its trades with the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The pound didn't fully rebound from its fall against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday: 1.4880 Swiss francs, up from 1.4852; 6.0270 French
francs, up from 6.0100; 1,776.75 Italian lire, up from 1,772.50;
and 1.4358 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4318.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6644 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6717 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
