<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Keep Edge over Democrats in Fund Raising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The committees helping elect
Senate and House Republicans keep a fund-raising edge over their
Democratic counterparts, although both political parties are
raising more money than they did during the last off-year
elections four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The National Republican Senatorial Committee reported raising
3.8 million dollars in March, including 1.2 million dollars in
"soft money," -- unregulated money which is supposed to be used
for party-building activities and issue-oriented advertising. That
same month, the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee raised
2.2 million dollars, including 770,854 dollars in "soft money."
</P>
<P>
Between January 1, 1997, and March 31, 1998, the NRSC took in
45 million dollars, as compared to 41 million dollars during the
same 15-month period four years ago. Contributions to the DSCC
also went up, from 14 million dollars during the 15-month period
beginning Jan. 1, 1993, to 23 million dollars during the
equivalent period beginning January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee raised 1.6
million dollars in March, including 463,531 dollars in "soft
money." That brought the committee's 15-month total to 19 million
dollars, compared with 12 million dollars in 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
The National Republican Congressional Committee, which files on
a different schedule, earlier reported raising 43 million dollars
in the 15-month period that began January 1, 1997, almost three
times the 15 million dollars the committee collected during the
same period in 1993-94, the last time members of Congress ran in a
non-presidential election year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
