<HEADLINE> U.S., Greek Officials Discuss Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. State Department's
special coordinator for Cyprus, Thomas Miller, discussed Thursday
with Greek Foreign Undersecretary Yiannos Kranidiotis ways of
settling the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a statement after Thursday night's talks, Miller,
who arrived here later Thursday, said that the American initiative
for a resolution of the Cyprus problem was under the aegis of the
United Nations and aimed at the attainment of a bizonal,
bicommunal, federal scheme.
</P>
<P>
He said that U.S. President's special emissary for Cyprus
Richard Holbrooke, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
himself believed that the current period was the most appropriate
for an intensive effort to resolve the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Miller regarded the resumption of negotiations between Cypriot
president Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash as "a matter of substance."
</P>
<P>
He said that Holbrooke and himself would visit Cyprus on May 1
to have discussions with the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Kranidiotis voiced Greece's support for the U.S.
initiative, saying that the initiative should be in the framework
of U.N. efforts and the Security Council resolutions about Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the quest for a bizonal, bicommunal federation
should enjoy the "broadest possible support."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive coup
backed by Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
