<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Complete Ban on All Tests for Nuclear Weapons Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Laboratory-based nuclear
weapons testing undermines Non-Proliferation Treaty commitments
and they should be banned totally, urged energy and environmental
research experts on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After the Cold War, treaties have been signed for arms
reduction and dismantlement, but some nuclear weapons states have
repeatedly indicated that they have no intention of pursuing total
nuclear disarmament, Arjun Makhijani, President of the Institute
for Energy and Environmental Research, said at a press briefing at
the National Press Club in Washing, D.C.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and Russia still have huge arsenals on
hair-trigger alert at a time when command and control systems in
Russia may be deteriorating," Makhijani said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, nuclear weapons states are continuing to develop
nuclear weapons, he said. Under its stockpile Stewardship and
Management program, the United States intends to retain huge teams
of designers and give them research tools that will maintain a
high level of "exciting" and challenging scientific projects
related to nuclear weapons design.
</P>
<P>
He said that the military laboratory programs by the United
States, France and Russia put the Comprehensive Test Ban treaty
(CTBT) in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that laboratory fusion programs could
result in new types of nuclear weapons being created. Besides new
designs of thermonuclear weapons, these programs raise the
possibility of new types of nuclear weapons that do not use
plutonium or highly enriched uranium.
</P>
<P>
These weapons may take the form of pure fusion weapons, that
is, nuclear weapons that only have a thermonuclear component.
Weapons that have a thermonuclear component that triggers a
fission component made of widely available uranium-238 may also be
developed. Such developments may occur both as a result of
military programs and of programs that are now stated to be for
non-military applications only, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the CTBT does not make any exception for nuclear fusion
explosions, or for peaceful research. It not only prohibits
nuclear explosion, but also requires parties to prevent them from
occurring under their jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
However, several laboratory fusion programs in both nuclear
weapons states as well as in non-nuclear weapons states have the
potential of violating the CTBT, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Makhijani said, given the immense consequences of the
development of pure fusion weapons, an indefinite delay of planned
Magnetized Target Fusion (MTF) experiments and a hold on the
construction fo large facilities designed to achieve ignition is
necessary.
</P>
<P>
"In the event that the projects are not halted, the United
States, France, Germany and Japan should announce now the
restraints they will appear to be a minimal commitment that these
countries ought to be willing to make," said Makhijani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
