<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- British Petroleum will invest 250-300 million U.S.
dollars in Venezuela to remodel and construct 350 service stations
in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The multinational firm has invested 700 million dollars in
Venezuela since 1993 to the present in exploration. The figure
will reach one billion dollars by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Heavy rains in the past weeks have affected the
Uruguayan rice harvest by flooding 2,500 hectares of cultivated
land.
</P>
<P>
The Programming, Agriculture and Livestock Policy Office
estimated that rain has reduced the yield by 20 percent, which was
calculated at 800,000 tons of rice.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina became one of the main destinations of
foreign investment in Latin America during the first quarter of
this year, followed by Mexico and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The three countries received about 5.67 billion dollars, 84
percent of the total during this period.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean fishing production was reduced by 40.5
percent to 1.25 million tons during the first quarter of this
year, compared with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Fishing Ministry announced that the catch of anchovies
registered the biggest drop by 70.7 percent to 156,470 tons.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Unemployment grew 179 percent in Brazil in the past
seven years to 3.26 million people, the Brazilian Institute of
Geography and statistics said.
</P>
<P>
Every year 951,400 new jobs are created in Brazil, but not
enough for the entire population.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Banking Fund for the Protection of Savings
in Mexico will sell the Camino Real hotel chain, which was formed
by 15 deluxe hotels in Mexico and one in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The banking fund, a state organization, said that four of the
hotels, which are assets of the Banco Union, are operated under a
bank contract and have a total of 3,828 hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
Authorities expect the process to conclude in the next six
months.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panamanian banana exports earned 42.9 million
dollars during the first quarter of this year, a 16.5 percent drop
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce and Industries Direction of the Commerce and
Industries Ministry said exports from the Pacific zone were
reduced by 38 percent and the biggest decrease reached 61.9
percent in March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
