<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Successful in Curbing Imports of Harmful Wastes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the largest trade
center in China, has made progress in curbing illegal imports of
harmful material from foreign countries in the past year.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, a total of 840,000 tons of re-usable wastes came
throug the Shanghai port, and the local Customs office did not
report findings of any illegal and harmful objects among them.
</P>
<P>
However, between July of 1995 and May of 1996, the Shanghai
Customs office uncovered cases involving imports of harmful
wastes, mainly from Europe and North America, such as waste
plastic bags, used rubber gloves, soft drink bottles and used film.
</P>
<P>
The latest finding shows that the local authorities have put a
halt to illicit imports, said local Customs officers.
</P>
<P>
This came as a result of the joint efforts from the local
Customs, commodity inspection as well as environmental
departments.
</P>
<P>
Chinese law stipulates that import of harmful wastes is an
illegal act, and the country has issued regulations specifying
that imports of wastes must be approved by the state environmental
bureau, go through inspections and examinations by local
functionaries before being let in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
