<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Slovenia, Hungary to Build Road Leading to Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Italy, Slovenia and Hungary agreed
Thursday to establish a joint authority to oversee the
construction of a road-rail link between the northeastern Italian
city of Trieste with the Ukrainian capital Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Italian Premier Romano Prodi, Hungarian Prime Minister Gyula
Horn and their Slovenian counterpart Janez Drnovsek signed the
agreement at their summit meeting here.
</P>
<P>
The joint authority, which will be based in Trieste, will plan,
finance and execute the project.
</P>
<P>
The proposed road-rail link, to pass through the Slovenian
capital Ljubljana and the Hungarian capital Budapest, is part of
the "Corridor 5" project to create a major transport artery linking
western and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
These three countries formed the Trilateral Pact in October
1996 within the framework of the Central European Initiative. It
aims to promote wide-ranging cooperation between them and
ultimately to promote stability in central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Trilateral Pact hopes that Corridor 5 will eventually run
all the way from Barcelona, Spain, to Kiev. Corridor 5 is supposed
to compete with another planned cross-Europe route connecting
Paris, Berlin and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
In fact, work has begun on parts of the Trieste-Kiev route, but
progress has slowed down due to financial problems.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government vowed to fund its part of the
initiative, said Trieste Mayor Riccardo Illy. Italy hopes the
stretch between Trieste and Budapest will be completed early in
the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan says U.S. Debts Hurt UN Peace-keeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Kofi Annan, Secretary-General
of the United Nations, said on Thursday the United States was
hurting the U.N.'s peacekeeping efforts by refusing to pay its
arrears.
</P>
<P>
The United States' indebtedness to the United Nations, which
now totals 1.5 billion U.S. dollars, is also poisoning
international relations, Annan said in a speech to about 4,000
people at Rice University in Houston.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who is on the final day of a three-day trip to
California and Texas, said: "By withholding the payments the U.S.
is provoking friends and foe alike."
</P>
<P>
According to news reports reaching here, Annan said the U.N.
had been unable to repay nations such as Fiji and Bangladesh for
providing soldiers for peacekeeping operations in the western
Sahara, which in turn made it difficult to get them for other
operations.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. behavior is destroying trust among nations and this is a
very serious charge," Annan said. "It does impede our ability to
function."
</P>
<P>
While in Houston, Annan met with former U.S. Secretary of State
James Baker and former President George Bush. They have both
supported U.S. involvement in the United Nations and Baker, in
particular, has called for payment of the U.S. debt.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, U.S. Ambassador Bill Richardson warned that
the United States could lose its vote in the United Nations by the
end of the year unless the debt issue is resolved.
</P>
<P>
Testifying before the House Appropriation Subcommittee, he said
the Clinton administration remains open to any compromise that
would separate U.N. funding from U.S. payments to family-planning
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said passage of the request for payment of most of
the 1.3 billion U.S. dollars it owes the organization by the end
of May would open the way for talks this summer on reducing the
annual U.S. contribution from 25 percent of the U.N. budget to 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
"Failure to pass the necessary legislation in time will cause
us to squander this unique opportunity and we will be unable to
reopen the scales of assessment (talks) until the fall of 2000,"
he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
