<HEADLINE> Investors Say Infrastructure Improves in Hainan (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Tonio Takazaki, general manager of
the Hainan Toyo Huisan Kaisha Ltd., a Japanese aquatic products
venture on China's Hainan province, says that he is impressed with
the improvement of the island's infrastructure over the past ten
years.
</P>
<P>
His company's initial investment was three million US dollars,
on an aquatic products farm which covers 53.3 hectares of
land. Later on he put another 10 million US dollars into the
venture, and now the company made 10 million US dollars worth of
exports a year. And, it was selected as a successul model for all
overseas-funded enterprises in the country.
</P>
<P>
But, ten years ago, when Hainan was just designated as a
province, overseas investors like Takazaki were very disappointed
and annoyed by the inconveniences caused by power shortages, and
terrible telephone and traffic conditions.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government was determined to change the
situation and has since worked out policies, giving top priority to
improvement of infrastructure.
</P>
