<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Grows 7.2 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's economic growth in the
first quarter this year slowed down to 7.2 percent on a
year-on-year basis, the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) said here
this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) totaled 1,589.9 billion yuan
in the three months, SSB spokesman Qiu Xiaohua told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Inflation was almost zero during the period, with the consumer
price index (CPI) rising just 0.3 percent over the corresponding
period of last year and the retail price index (RPI) falling by
1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy grew 8.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"The overall situation of the Chinese economy is basically
normal," said Qiu, while pointing out that a most prominent
problem confronting the economy still lies with the sliding
economic efficiency of the country's industries.
</P>
<P>
"But we can count on a full realization of the annual economic
growth of eight percent this year, with the deepening of the
reform drive and a successful expansion of the domestic demand,"
stressed the SSB spokesman.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown showed that agriculture, industry, and service
sector grew four percent, 7.8 percent, and seven percent over the
same period last year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China used a total of 8.596 billion US dollars of overseas
direct investment during the first three months of this year, up
9.7 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last month, the state foreign exchange reserve
had reached 140.6 billion US dollars, 700 million US dollars more
than at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China registered a trade surplus of 10.64 billion
US dollars, with exports up by 13.2 percent to 40.24 billion
US dollars and imports up by 2.7 percent to 29.6 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"From a long-term point of view, China's economy has a solid
material basis and adequate support from the national policies,"
Qiu said.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure China's economy to grow eight percent this year,
the whole nation needs to fully implement the related policies,
especially those designed to stimulate domestic demand growth,
optimize the economic structure and increase efficiency, "
the SSB spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
