<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investors Say Hainan Infrastructure Improves (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the past decade, the province has spent 118 billion yuan
(14.2 billion US dollars) on fixed assets, which have grown 31
percent annually.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, its electricity generating capacity was
1.56 million kilowatts, and it supplied 3.4 billion kilowatts
annually, five times the amount in 1987, something that has
allowed many new industrial cities to be built.
</P>
<P>
There were only 3 berths for 10,000-dwt ships in Hainan in
1987, but now there are 12, providing links with 20 countries and
regions and a port handling capacity of 10 million tons at the end
of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, the island has built 5,000 kilometers of
highways, bringing the total to 17,000 kilometers, and putting it
in the first place in terms of highway density in China.
</P>
<P>
The province also has a new airport in Sanya in the southern
part of the island, a larger airport in the capital, at least 130
air routes and 450 flights each week, linking it with many major
world cities.
</P>
<P>
The province now has over 10,000 long-distance telephone lines
linking it with over 2,000 cities and towns in China and over 230
cities in the other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
This has brought in 8,000 enterprises with 7.5 billion US
dollars worth of overseas funding and over 19,000 enterprises with
50 billion yuan in investment from other Chinese regions to the
island province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
