<HEADLINE> Zedillo Denies Market Economy Causes Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo denied Thursday that the market economy has caused poverty
to millions of Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
He said that poverty is a result of many years of statist,
populist, and paternalist policies which oppose market economy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 24th National Assembly of the Mexican
Foundation for Rural Development, Zedillo said he is determined to
stabilize the market economy with a growing investment in human
resources.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would allot resources for the Alliance
for Agriculture worth 2.632 billion pesos (about 317 million U.S.
dollars), 50 percent more than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The president hoped that the growing social spending would
provide the poor opportunities of progress and well-being and also
promote equality and justice.
</P>
<P>
The worst problem for the Mexican agriculture is that the poor
cannot produce enough to help themselves out of poverty. Zedillo
said it is a permanent and complex vicious circle that bars them
from being well-off.
</P>
<P>
"Mexicans must build an economy with a human face in which the
economic growth will not be an end, but only the necessary means
to advance in social justice," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
