<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Labor Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Labor Minister Farid
Ayales resigned his post Thursday after being charged with the
illegal administration of money collected from Nicaraguan
immigrant workers.
</P>
<P>
Ayales said he had already tendered his resignation to
President Jose Maria Figueres and he denied the charges in a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Ministry created a work card to legalize the presence
of hundreds of thousands of undocumented Nicaraguan workers in
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
The measure had the support of the Nicaraguan authorities.
However, the Costa Rican Public Attorney's Office conducted an
investigation into abuses reported in the case.
</P>
<P>
The minister reportedly created an agency in charge of
collecting 5,000 colons (almost 20 dollars) to process the
document, but the practice was challenged by several sectors.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica had promised to provide 50,000 working cards to
Nicaraguans when they fulfilled certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the Nicaraguan workers in Costa Rica have
received working cards, said informed sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
