<HEADLINE> Serbia Says No to International Mediation in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- In a referendum held on
Thursday, nearly five million voters in Serbia, Yugoslavia, gave
an overwhelming "no" to international mediation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results for the referendum showed that about 93
percent of the voters opposed foreign interference in Yugoslavia's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The voters expressed support in the principled stand of
Yugoslavian and Serbian leaders that Kosovo is an inseparable part
of Serbia and the issue is an internal affair and should be
settled by political means, the Politika daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a polling booth in Belgrade, Yugoslavian President
Slobodan Milosevic said all nationalities in the country could and
must solve their problems by themselves for common interests.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic urged leaders of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo to open
talks with Serbian representatives as soon as possible, and hoped
that the Serbian authorities be fully sincere in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo have repeatedly refused to
meet with the Serbian government delegation unless foreign
representatives are present.
</P>
<P>
At least 80 ethnic Albanians and Serb policemen have been
killed since ethnic conflicts broke out in the Serbian province in
late February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
