<HEADLINE> No Problem for China's Economy to Grow 8 Percent: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China will face no big
difficulties in achieving an eight percent economic growth this
year, a spokesman for the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) said here
this morning.
</P>
<P>
The national economy increased steadily in the first quarter,
and it will further pick up in the remaining quarters of this
year, spokesman Qiu Xiaohua said at a press conference in
responding to a question by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
The existing material conditions are the most favorable for
economic expansion since China started to implement the policy of
reform and opening-up.
</P>
<P>
The bottleneck posed by energy, communications, and raw
materials sectors has been obviously alleviated, he added.
</P>
<P>
Good agricultural harvests for three consecutive years also
provided conditions for this, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange reserve has topped 140 billion US dollars, and
bank deposits exceeded the loans in the past four years, offering
another advantage to this, he added.
</P>
<P>
Qiu said that the inflation problem has been obviously solved,
with prices continuing to go down.
</P>
<P>
And the central government has made a series of clear and
appropriate policies for control of macro-economy. Now efforts are
being intensified to readjust economic structure, deepen reform,
and stimulate domestic demand, he said.
</P>
<P>
"All these constitute a favorable macro-economic environment
for achieving the goal of an eight percent growth of the national
economy this year," Qiu said, adding that immediate efforts should
be made to achieve higher economic performance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
