<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China in Solid Position to Enhance Economy: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China is in a solid position to
stimulate its economy and absorb an external shock, a senior World
Bank (WB) official said here today.
</P>
<P>
While economic growth weakened in the first quarter this year,
an acceleration is expected to occur gradually some time later in
light of investment increase, Kathie Krumm, Chief for Economics of
the WB Resident Mission in China, said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
China's State Statistics Bureau (SSB) told a press conference here
this morning that economic growth slowed down to 7.2 percent in
the first three months this year, compared to an average of 8.8
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"Recent macroeconomic trend has added to concerns at the end
of 1997 that growth is significantly weakening, in particular,
that domestic demand is weak," Kathie Krumm said.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been compounded by a deceleration in growth
in net external demand stemming from the Asia regional crisis --
albeit less than expected so far, she said.
</P>
<P>
However, the chief economist held that the reforms of the last
couple of years, in particular, macroeconomic stabilization and
foreign exchange management, have provided favorable conditions
for China's efforts to promote economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Chinese government has recently taken measures
to expand investment, she said that "modest domestic demand
stimulus including increased investment is appropriate to help
boost the economy."
</P>
<P>
"This is essential to employment expansion for facilitating
state-owned enterprise restructuring and continued labor
mobility," she said.
</P>
<P>
"While China's economy is like a huge ship whose direction
cannot be changed within a one-quarter adjustment, the
acceleration will appear in coming quarters gradually, if
investment expands," she said.
</P>
<P>
She suggested that the Chinese government use levers to boost
the economy that are consistent with the structural reform agenda,
including reliance on the financial sector to identify efficient
projects and tapping of domestic savings through alternative
channels.
</P>
<P>
"We support the government's intentions to stimulate the
economy in a timely manner and its commitment to continue to
promote the structural agenda during this process," the WB
economist said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
