<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Wants to Settle Crisis Through </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the
Anti-Taliban Northern Alliance, who arrived here Thursday evening
for the proposed face-to-face meeting with the Taliban scheduled
for Saturday, said they wanted to settle disputed issues with the
militia through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen at the Islamabad airport, the coordinator of
the nine-member delegation of the Northern Alliance, Abdul Rahim,
said they would be participating in the meeting of the Steering
Committee with sincerity.
</P>
<P>
Rahim said the proposed talks would focus on the setting up of
a Ulema (religious scholars) Commission, as well as dealing with
the issues of ceasefire, exchange of prisoners of war and
provision of aid to the affected Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan opposition delegation was met at the airport by N.
Gobi, head of the U.N. Afghan mission in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Gobi said the modalities of the Steering Committee meeting will
be decided on Friday by the representatives of the Taliban and the
Northern Alliance themselves.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on the duration of the talks, Gobi
said: "It depends on how the process moves forward."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. officials had a hectic day Thursday preparing
ground work for the Steering Committee meeting, which would seek
ways of achieving permanent peace in the war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia has sent a five-member delegation led by
Wakil Ahmed for the forthcoming meeting.
</P>
<P>
The assistant secretary general of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC), Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, is scheduled to
arrive here on Friday for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is being held under the auspices of the United
Nations and OIC.
</P>
<P>
It would be the first face-to-face meeting between the Taliban
and the Northern Alliance since September 1996 when the Taliban
took over the Afghan capital of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Bringing the rival factions to the negotiating table has been
deemed a major diplomatic achievement of Pakistan, in
collaboration with the Iranian authorities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
