<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Focus on Economic Growth, Real Sector in Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth and the problems
of the real sector in Thailand will be the focus of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) during its next review of the
country's economy, the Nation newspaper reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda, returning
Thursday from the G-22 finance ministers' meeting in Washington,
said the IMF will send representatives to Thailand between May 4
and 14 to assess the economic scenario and progress in
implementation of the IMF bailout conditions.
</P>
<P>
An important factor in the next review is economic growth, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Growth is hampered because the real sector has been affected
by baht volatility, liquidity crunch and a sharp contraction of
consumer purchasing power," Tarrin was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has predicted that Thailand's economy this year would
experience negative growth of between 3 and 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tarrin said the IMF will also delve deeper into the
real sector problems, and there will be new measures concerning
financial institutions' stabilization.
</P>
<P>
Thai manufacturers, exporters and some academics have long
complained of high interest rates and the liquidity crisis,
blaming them on the government-IMF imposition of a tight monetary
policy.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, deputy prime minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi and other members of the Council of Economic
Ministers Monday adopted supplementary measures to encourage
state-owned banks to lend.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin declined to comment on the possibility that the IMF will
allow Thailand to relax the current austere monetary policies in
order to lower the interest rates and increase money supply.
</P>
<P>
Whether the IMF will ease the austerity program depends on the
readiness of Thailand and the results of existing measures, Tarrin
said.
</P>
<P>
There are signs of improvement in investor confidence, with
foreign capital returning and the baht becoming more stable,
Tarrin added.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister also said that he met IMF Managing
Director Michel Camdessus to discuss topics related to the fourth
letter of intent to the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
