<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Leads March to Mark Holocaust Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu led thousands of people in a march in southern Poland on
Thursday to remember the six million Jews killed in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
Senior Polish leaders including Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek
joined Netanyahu in the march, reported the Polish Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the march, including 6,500 young Jews from
40 countries and 1,000 survivors of the Holocaust, walked three
kilometers from Auschwitz to Birkenau, a route once taken by many
of those who were then gassed and burned in vast crematoria.
</P>
<P>
Nazi troops killed up to 1.5 million people, most of them Jews
brought in from all over Europe, in the Auschwitz-Birkenau death
camp.
</P>
<P>
A powerful Jewish state provided the sole guarantee against the
slaughter of Jews, said Netanyahu near the ruins of the massive
gas chambers and crematoria at Birkenau.
</P>
<P>
"A Jewish state would have made it impossible to kill millions
of Jews, indeed to kill any Jews with impunity," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony, called the March of the Living, was organized
regularly since 1988 to help young Jews to comprehend the
Holocaust. Thursday was Israel's Holocaust Martyrs and Heroes
Remembrance Day.
</P>
<P>
Participants will go on to Israel for next week's celebrations
marking the 50th anniversary of the founding of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu arrived in Poland shortly before the march for a
20-hour working visit. He went to Warsaw for talks with Buzek on
international issues and bilateral relations after the ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
