<HEADLINE> China's Exports to Non-Asian Areas Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's exports to non-Asian
regions in the world jumped in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) Qiu Xiaohua
told a press conference this morning that China's exports to North
America, Europe, Latin America and Africa grew by 21.9 percent,
29.6 percent, 40.1 percent and 33.9 percent, respectively in the
three months over the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
China has registered a 13.2 percent increase in total exports
during January to March over the same period of last year, with a
trade surplus of over 10 billion US dollars in the period.
</P>
<P>
However, Qiu said that exports to Asia grew at a lower rate due
to the financial turmoil that hit many countries and region in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
SSB statistics showed that exports to Asia grew by only 4.8
percent in the first quarter of this year over the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
China's exports to ASEAN countries, Japan and Republic of Korea
dropped by 17.6 percent, 1.7 percent and 22.5 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Qiu said that the increase of China's total exports was a
result of the efforts that the country took to diversify its
overseas market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
