<HEADLINE> Economists Confident in Growth Acceleration (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's mainstream economists
today say that they are confident of the eight percent growth of
the country's economy this year, despite a further slowdown in
the past three months.
</P>
<P>
In separate interviews with Xinhua today, a number of prominent
economists shared the view that the trend of economic deceleration
will be reversed later this year as the government has adopted a
series of measures to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistics Bureau (SSB) announced this morning that
the national economy grew by 7.2 percent in the first quarter this
year, compared to 8.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"Such a slowdown was due to the lagging effect of the battle
against inflation in the previous years as well as the negative
impact on China's exports by the Southeast Asian financial
crisis," said Liu Shucheng, a leading economist with the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences (CASS).
</P>
<P>
But since the end of last year, the central authorities have
made appropriate policy readjustments, concentrating on
stimulating domestic demand to ensure a steady economic growth,
Liu pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Our model analysis indicates that investment growth is
accelerating gradually and most likely to surpass 15 percent
throughout this year, which will lay a solid ground for an eight
percent economic growth this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the SSB, fixed-asset investment grew 10.3 percent
in the first quarter, while foreign direct investment rose by
around 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
