<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Faces Highest Risk of Dengue in 40 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The incidence of dengue fever in
Thailand is expected to reach its highest level in 40 years this
year, affecting some 300,000 people, the Ministry of Public Health
has warned.
</P>
<P>
Friday's Bangkok Post quoted Public Health Minister Rakkiat
Sukthana as saying that changes in climate as a result of the
global warming effects of the El Nino and inadequate preventive
measures are to blame.
</P>
<P>
Usually dengue fever occurs only during the monsoon season. But
since last year, it has been escalating through the cool and hot
season, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In the first three months of this year, the disease claimed 31
lives and infected 10,197 people, a three-fold increase over the
previous corresponding period when it took eight lives and
infected 3,280 people.
</P>
<P>
Reports of patients treated in state hospitals show that 70-75
percent of patients with dengue fever are between 5 and 14 years
of age.
</P>
<P>
An expert at the Communicable Disease Control Department said
most doctors tend to overlook the possible occurrence of dengue
fever among older children or young adults and often suspect them
of being infected with other diseases.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Permanent Secretary of Public Health Vinai Viriyakijja
said that since most infections occur in schools and communities,
a mass campaign to destroy mosquitoes and sources of their
breeding will be launched between June 15 and 19 in 800 districts
throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for More Agricultural Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China has called for strengthening
regional food and agricultural cooperation and expressed readiness
to join hands with FAO and other nations in making new
contributions to improving agriculture and food security in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a two-day ministerial meeting of the 24th Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) Regional Conference for Asia and
the Pacific, Chinese Vice Minister of Agriculture Wan Baorui, who
led a nine-member delegation to the conference, urged Asian and
Pacific countries to strengthen economic and technical cooperation
in the field of food and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He also asked developed countries in the region to provide
necessary assistance to agricultural development in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Asia and Pacific region has witnessed rapid growth in its
food and agricultural production and further improvement of its
food security in recent years, he said. However, he noted, the
region is still faced with an arduous task of developing food and
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He stated that Asia and Pacific countries should intensify
their food and agricultural production in the face of the present
unfavorable situation arising from the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Asian and Pacific countries should attach
great importance to food and agricultural production, increase
inputs through multiple channels and speed up the development of
agricultural technology.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the region should also pay special attention to
the development and utilization of limited agricultural resources
by engaging in integrated development and diversified farming
activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the holding of the World Food Summit in
1996 has opened a new chapter in mankind's efforts to eradicate
hunger and poverty and improve food security.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister emphasized that the Chinese government has
always attached great importance to agriculture and food security
and regards feeding the people as its primary concern. After the
World Food Summit, he pointed out, the Chinese government has
taken policy measures aimed at strengthening and protecting
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He told the conference that in 1997, China produced 492.5
million tons of grains, 53.54 million tons of meat, 35.61 million
tons of fish and other seafood and 50.54 million tons of fruit.
</P>
<P>
He said China will continue to uphold the policy of putting
agriculture on the top of its economic agenda and deepening rural
reforms.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that with the unswerving efforts of its people,
China would be able to realize the goals set for the country's
agricultural and rural economic development.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which began Monday with a three-day senior
officials meeting and a two-day ministerial meeting, is the first
regional gathering of agricultural ministers since the 1996 World
Food Summit in Rome, Italy. Attending the meetings are 150
representatives from 26 FAO member countries in Asia and the
Pacific, U.N. agencies and non-governmental organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
