<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Grows 7.2 Percent in First Quarter (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's economic growth slowed
down to 7.2 percent in the first quarter this year, compared to
the annual rate of eight percent in 1997, the State Statistics
Bureau (SSB) said here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) totaled 1,589.9 billion yuan
during the Janurary-March period, SSB spokesman Qiu Xiaohua told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Inflation continued the downward trend, with the consumer price
index (CPI) rising only 0.3 percent over the corresponding period
of last year and the retail price index (RPI) falling by 1.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The overall situation of the Chinese economy is basically
normal," Qiu said, While pointing out that a most prominent
problem confronting the economy still lies with the sliding
economic efficiency of the country's industries.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown showed that the nation's agriculture, industry,
and service sector grew four percent, 7.8 percent, and seven
percent over the same period last year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The output value of the nation's industrial sector hit 442.1
billion yuan during the period, with the growth rate dropping 2.8
percent to 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The economic efficiency of the industrial enterprises
decreased, with the total industrial profits plunging by 82.8
percent during the first two months.
</P>
<P>
"But we can still count on a full realization of the annual
economic growth of eight percent this year, with the deepening of
the reform drive and a successful expansion of the domestic
demand," stressed the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In separate interviews with Xinhua today, a number of prominent
economists shared the view that the trend of economic deceleration
will be reversed later this year as the government has adopted a
series of measures to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of last year, the central authorities have made
appropriate policy readjustments, concentrating on stimulating
domestic demand to ensure a steady economic growth, noted Liu
Shucheng, a leading economist with the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"Our model analysis indicates that investment growth is
accelerating gradually and most likely to surpass 15 percent
throughout this year, which will lay a solid ground for an eight
percent economic growth this year," Liu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First SAARC Information Ministers Meeting to Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Information ministers from the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) will
begin their first meeting here Saturday to enhance cooperation in
media communications and information among member states of the
regional organization.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, to be opened by Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina, is "the curtainraiser" of this year's SAARC Colombo
summit, Pakistani Information Minister Mushahid Hussain said upon
his arrival on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will "formulate a regional outlook based on shared
vision, common interest and mutual benefit of the people in the
region," the national news agency BSS said.
</P>
<P>
SAARC Secretary General Naeem U Hasan, who also arrived here
Thursday, said the meeting is important as it is part of the
process to upgrade the level of cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Information ministers from Bangladesh, Pakistan, India, Sri
Lanka and India will attend the meeting, while the Maldives will
be represented by a three-member delegation and Bhutan by its
Charge d'Affairs in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC, established in December 1985, groups Bangladesh,
Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
</TEXT>
