<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia C. Bank Reiterates No Foreign Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia (BOZ), a
central bank, has reiterated that it has no intentions of
reintroducing foreign exchange controls, state-owned Times of
Zambia reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Thursday, according to the paper,
BOZ spokesman Kabinga Pande announced that the country's current
liberalized foreign exchange scenario will continue and no
measures inconsistent with this will be introduced.
</P>
<P>
He said the liberalized market environment is a cornerstone of
the Zambian government's economic policy and that this policy is
still in place.
</P>
<P>
These remarks followed earlier reports this week that quoted a
senior official of the central bank saying BOZ is to reintroduce
foreign exchange regulations.
</P>
<P>
The BOZ spokesman asked the public and the business community
not to panic as the government and the central bank has no
intention of deviating from current economic policies.
</P>
<P>
He stressed hat there are no plans whatsoever to revert to any
kind of controls.
</P>
<P>
Zambia abandoned its foreign exchange controls in the early
1990s when the country began to implement its liberalized market
policies.
</P>
<P>
However, the country since the end of last year has
experienced a critical shortage of foreign exchange due to high
demand and low inflows from the copper sale and it is now runing
out of its foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Zambian Kwacha continues depreciating from
1,330 last October to 1,900 against U.S. Dollars this week. The
central bank seems to have no means to curb such a situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
