<HEADLINE> Russian Passenger Plane Catches Fire in Istanbul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A Russian passenger plane caught
fire at the Ataturk Airport in Istanbul early Friday, but causing
no casualties, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Ilyushin-62 plane from Istanbul to Alma Ata, Kazakhstan,
was found in fire at its tail part before take-off at 00:25 local
time (2125 GMT Thursday), the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The fire forced emergency evacuation of all 64 passengers and
nine crew members on board. An explosion occurred in the right
motor of the plane soon after the evacuation, according to the
news agency.
</P>
<P>
It said a Turkish fire brigade poured six tonnes of chemical
materials and 30 tonnes of water to prevent the fire from
spreading to the plane depot, which contained 50 tonnes of fuel.
</P>
<P>
The fire, which started in the cargo hold, cause serious
damages to the four motors of the plane, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
Investigations into the cause of the fire are underway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
