<HEADLINE> ASEAN-China Trade Increases 22 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Trade between China and the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) amounted to 25
billion U.S. dollars in 1997, up 22 percent from 1996, the
Jakarta-based ASEAN Secretariat said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"However, Chinese investments in ASEAN are much lower than
ASEAN investments in China and only in recent years did Chinese
investors begin to make their presence felt in the ASEAN region,"
it said in a statement released here.
</P>
<P>
To improve Sino-ASEAN economic ties, China will send a
delegation comprising senior representatives of major state-owned
enterprises to several ASEAN countries before the end of the
month, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The delegation will look into economic opportunities with a
view to increasing Chinese investments and economic relations with
ASEAN members," it said.
</P>
<P>
According to its tentative itinerary, the delegation will visit
Manila, Kuala Lumpur and Bangkok. The trip would be organized by
the China Council for Promotion of International Trade.
</P>
<P>
In addition, leading Chinese entrepreneurs from the All-China
Federation of Industry and Commerce would organize an ASEAN tour
in May, it said.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat said China has provided Thailand with 1 billion
 dollars of soft loans and Indonesia with 600 million dollars of
soft loans and export credits to help ease the liquidity squeeze
in the two ASEAN economies.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
