<HEADLINE> Nepali Cabinet Minister Tenders Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- In a first blow to Prime
Minister Girija Prasad Koirala who took office a week ago, one of
his cabinet ministers has been forced to tender resignation for
failing to effectively deal with corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
Government sources confirmed Friday that Khum Bahadur Khadka,
minister for forest and soil conservation and supplies, on
Thursday offered to resign under pressure from MPs of his own
Nepali Congress (NC) party.
</P>
<P>
Khadka, who was home minister in the former government led by
Surya Bahadur Thapa, has been held responsible by his colleagues
for the upsurge in corruption and smuggling in the country.
</P>
<P>
Most MPs of the NC boycotted parliament sessions for a second
straight day Thursday to vent their anger against the induction of
tainted MPs into the cabinet, The Kathmandu Post said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Amar Raj Kaini, minister of state for industry and labor, has
been refusing to take the oath of office since he was picked up by
Koirala Tuesday in his expansion of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Before Koirala expanded his cabinet, MPs from his own party,
the NC, had pressured him to refrain from inducting MPs perceived
as corrupt.
</P>
<P>
The Kathmandu Post said some agitated NC MPs on Thursday
gathered at Koirala's official residence and reminded him of the
NC General Committee resolution adopted last year which directs
the party leadership to deal with corruption with an iron hand and
stresses the necessity to maintain a clean image of the party when
in government.
</P>
<P>
The present government, which came to power on April 15, is a
minority government of the NC, the largest party in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Koirala, who is president and parliamentary leader of the NC,
had agreed to convene a formal meeting of the parliamentary party
on Saturday to "sort out the issue," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted sources close to Koirala as saying he could
well dismiss a couple of more ministers in the days to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
