<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Expanding Tehran-Tokyo Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran has called for a
comprehensive program to promote long-term Tehran-Tokyo relations
and cooperation in political, economic and cultural fields, the
official Islamic Republic News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting Japanese Deputy Foreign Minister
Masahiko Komura on Thursday, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi hailed the historical relations of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that the bilateral ties will be consolidated and
expanded, adding that Iran and Japan share ample common grounds
for attaining the goal.
</P>
<P>
Exchange of delegations and continued consultations would be
effective in that direction, Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
The two officials also discussed the problems faced by Iranians
in Japan, and issues in the Persian Gulf and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Komura said that his country has the political
will to expand relations with Iran. Tokyo is to increase exchange
of delegates to upgrade close cooperation with Tehran, he said.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of Japanese Foreign Minister Obuchi Keizo, Komura
invited Kharrazi to visit Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese official arrived here on Wednesday for a four-day
visit. He is to deliver a message from Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto to Iranian President Mohammad Khatami. 
