<HEADLINE> US Investors Plan to Open Firm in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A group of U.S. businessmen
visiting Uganda plan to establish a liaison firm in this east
African country, the New Vision newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Richard Williams, one of the 10-member team, was quoted as
saying Thursday that they are planning to create a company before
they leave for home next week.
</P>
<P>
The main fields they plan to invest are telecommunications,
fishery, agro-processing and solar systems, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Their ambitions are to create a village to produce fish, solar
energy equipment and video-conferencing facilities, said
Williams, a Uganda-born American.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. businessmen started their tour to the African country
last week. Most of them are Ugandan descendants.
</P>
<P>
This is the first American business mission touring Uganda
since Bill Clinton paid a visit to the African nation last month.
During his trip, Clinton pledged to create a new trade
partnership between the U.S. and Africa. 
</P>
