<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Light Rail Workers Strike Enters Second Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A strike by workers of the
Philippines' only Light Rail Transit (LRT) entered its second day
Friday with no relief in sight, stranding thousands of commuters
in Manila and nearby suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Police trucks were filled but they were not able to bring most
of the commuters to their destinations.
</P>
<P>
LRT General Manager Moises Tolentino assured the public that an
announcement on the resumption of LRT operations will be made
during the day.
</P>
<P>
He said that about 400 workers of the 14-year-old industry have
not joined the strike which began at 3 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
These non-strikers are believed to be the ones set to be
shielded in case train operation resumes.
</P>
<P>
The striking workers are asking for a 3,500-peso
across-the-board monthly salary increase this year and 3,000 pesos
a month in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The LRT management offered a 1,000-peso monthly pay raise for
1998 starting February and another 1,000 pesos in monthly wages
for 1999, but the striking workers rejected the offer.
</P>
<P>
Tolentino said the LRT spends about 45 percent of their annual
income on wages alone.
</P>
<P>
Last year, he said, the LRT had an income of 1.2 billion pesos,
and part of the income will be used for the operation of 28
additional air-conditioned coaches.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Labor and Employment is expected to issue a
return-to-work order Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
