<HEADLINE> S. African Army to Help Curb Taxi Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The South African army is
on standby and extra police units have been deployed in Soweto,
Johannesburg, to curb renewed clashes between taxi organizations,
the daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Two platoons of the South African National Defense Force,
numbering about 48 men, were waiting to be deployed Thursday
night to reinforce the police.
</P>
<P>
Four people have been killed in the clashes in Soweto this
week.
</P>
<P>
The Soweto violence, which coincides with a nationwide
resurgence in taxi warfare, has disrupted public transport in the
giant black township as many taxi owners have opted to keep their
vehicles off the roads.
</P>
<P>
Of the 61 people killed across the country so far this year,
40 died in Gauteng Province, where Soweto is situated, and eight
in Kwazulu-Natal.
</P>
<P>
Long-standing tensions between two rival groups in Pretoria --
the Federated Local and Long Distance Taxi Association and the
South African Local and Long Distance Taxi Association -- have
accounted for the high number of deaths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
