<HEADLINE> Nigeria Accuses U.S. of Politicizing Drug Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has accused the U.S. of
politicizing the west African country's drug problems, saying
that the continued decertification of Nigeria by the U.S. despite
all that the country has done makes the issue laughable.
</P>
<P>
Major-General Musa Bamaiyi, head of the National Drug Law
Enforcement Agency of Nigeria, said this at a press conference
Thursday in Abuja, during the 10th Summit of Heads of National
Drug Law Enforcement Agencies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"I think from every perspective, the U.S. has already
politicized the drug issues. So, whether we do very well or very
badly, it makes no difference to them, and the report will be the
same," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bamaiyi pointed out that "America is entitled to its opinion.
Nigeria as a sovereign nation is equally entitled to its own
opinion. The only sad aspect is that pointing accusing fingers
or exchanging such blames will never help resolve the global
program of action."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the two countries should identify their
differences and try to sort them out in the best interest of the
global action plan on drugs.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the press conference, Tony White, an official
from the United Nations Drug Control Program (UNDCP), promised
that the UNDCP will help African countries draw up necessary
legislations on money laundering and assets confiscation, which
he said is essential to stop the increasing drug trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
