<HEADLINE> Manila, Rebels to Resume Talks After May Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Peace negotiators of the
Philippine government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) ended another round of low-level talks Thursday and agreed
to meet again after the May 11 elections, a rebel leader said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF deputy chairman for political affairs,
said the two panels will meet on a still undetermined date after
the elections to study further pending proposals of the peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He said that due to stale discussions over the issue of
repositioning their respective combatants in Upper Minabay
village, Buldon, the southern province of Maguindanao, negotiators
decided to reset their meeting to come up with a more appropriate
decision on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said that if not because of the controversial Buldon
issue, negotiators might have undertaken the agenda on recognition
of MILF territories in Mindanao and the much-awaited formal talks
schedule in the just-concluded two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said they also anticipate a possible change of
government panel members in the next meeting "considering the
impending change of administration."
</P>
<P>
Jaafar, however, expressed optimism that whoever becomes the
next Philippine president, "the MILF is assured of continuity of
the peace talks." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
