<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Divorce Becomes Easier for S. Africans: Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Divorce has become cheaper
and easier for all South Africans following the passing of a new
divorce law which came into effect in early April, the daily
Sowetan reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 Divorce Courts Amendment Act, which came into
operation on April 6, makes provision for a divorce procedure
which is uncomplicated and affordable and does not enforce the
requirement of legal representation.
</P>
<P>
The act was amended to replace the Black Administration Act of
1929 and Amendment Act of 1929.
</P>
<P>
The latest law makes divorce courts, which were previously
accessible only to whites, open to all population groups
irrespective of race or financial status throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Palesa Sedibe-Ncholo, special adviser to the Minister of
Justice, was quoted as saying that the act had made the laws
relating to divorce uniform, meaning, any person had a choice to
approach either the High Court or the divorce courts in order to
obtain a divorce.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the act will reach out to the lower rungs of
the courts will make justice cheaper and accessible,"
Sedibe-Ncholo said.
</P>
<P>
"Where litigants are unable to get their own legal
presentation, the clerks and registrars of the courts, who have
been trained, will assist such litigants."
</P>
<P>
Last year, 31,000 couples were separated in South Africa's
High courts. A total of 7,500 were separated in divorce courts
in 1995-96. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
