<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Promulgate Privatization Law Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will promulgate a new law
on the privatization of state-owned enterprises by the end of the
month, Finance Minister Anthony Ani has said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said in Washington that the law to guide the
privatization exercise had been drafted while other aspects of
the privatization program, including the appointment of
consultants and investment banks and evaluations had been worked
upon.
</P>
<P>
Ani, who was in Washington to attend the spring meetings of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund said: "the
privatization strategy itself has been done and when the program
comes out, we will invite bids."
</P>
<P>
The minister said the privatization exercise will begin with
NITEL (Nigeria Telecommunications Corporation) as announced in
the 1998 budget by the government.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing guided privatization, we want to take on and do
it properly before we go onto others," Ani said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, finance is not the only factor in
choosing new investors for NITEL, instead, he said, Nigeria is
looking for core strategic investors with a combination of
expertise, managerial capacity and finance.
</P>
<P>
Besides NITEL, the National Electric Power Authority, as well
as the oil refineries, the petrochemical, bitumen, coal and
leisure sectors will all be privatized, the minister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
