<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Adopts New Population Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Thursday
released a new population policy, which places the population at
the center of all development strategies.
</P>
<P>
"The new policy corrects grave errors of the past by adopting
sustainable human development as the central theme," Welfare and
Population Development Minister Geraldine Fraser-Molekiti was
quoted as saying by local daily Business Day Friday.
</P>
<P>
The policy was seen as a major departure from past policies
which were "aimed at curtailing fertility through the provision
of contraceptive services."
</P>
<P>
"The new policy places population at the center of all
development strategies and regards population as the driving
force and the ultimate beneficiary of development,"
Fraser-Molekiti said.
</P>
<P>
It embraced the view that South Africans, especially women and
the youth, should be empowered to take control of their own
lives.
</P>
<P>
The policy outlines 24 strategies to be employed to address
population concerns. Areas covered include poverty reduction;
employment; education; migration and urbanization; health,
mortality and fertility; gender, women, youth and children;
coordination and capacity building for integrating population and
development planning; advocacy and population information,
education and communication and data collection and research.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary census results in South Africa indicated a
population of 37.9 million, four million fewer than expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker as Bond Price Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
weakened at the close Friday, with the banking index leading it
down.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries closed down 22.9 points, or 0.8 percent, at
2,854.9.
</P>
<P>
"It was a market where the buyers were prepared to stand out
and let the sellers stumble over each other," said Reynolds and
Co. broker Peter Struck.
</P>
<P>
Struck said a 111.7-point, or 1.82-percent, drop in the banking
index had led the fall. Bank stocks had fallen in response to
weaker global bond prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The banks are getting a bit of a pounding today, bonds came
out well and the American market started this off," Struck said.
</P>
<P>
All four major Australian banks were weaker. National Australia
Bank lost 43 cents to 22.92 Australian dollars on a heavy turnover
of 23.7 million shares and Westpac bank lost 33 cents to 10.69
Australian dollars while ANZ bank fell 20 cents to 11.4 Australian
dollars and Commonwealth Bank dropped 20 cents to 18.73 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the All Industrials Index lost 49.5 points, or 1.01
percent, to 4,875.7 and the All Resources Index lost 0.1 point, or
0.01 percent, to 1,245.7.
</P>
<P>
Among the major resources stocks, BHP dropped 16.1 cents to
15.459 Australian dollars on a turnover of 12 million shares while
Rio Tinto gained 40 cents to 22.3 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index failed to repeat Thursday's sharp rally and
finished down 6.1 points, or 0.43 percent, at 1,422.4.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, gold was trading at 313.2 U.S. dollars an ounce late
Friday, down from 313.35 U.S. dollars at Thursday night's close.
</P>
<P>
Overall, national turnover was 632.7 million shares, valued at
143.26 million U.S. dollars. Falls of 594 outnumbered rises of 495
stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
