<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Dips Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar dipped
lower in afternoon trading to finish near its lows for Friday.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed at 65.12 U.S. cents from 65.25 late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Stuart Moore, manager of foreign exchange trading of St. George
Bank, said the market finished in negative territory after opening
on Friday morning with an initial rise.
</P>
<P>
The local currency began the session at 65.35 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"The market is focusing on the Japanese package, due out in a
few hours," Moore said.
</P>
<P>
The waterfront dispute continued Friday as stevedoring company
Patrick went to the High Court in a new bid to overturn Thursday
night's ruling by the full bench of the Federal Court, which
upheld an earlier order to the company to reinstate 1,400
unionists fired two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
High Court Judge Ken Hayne Friday extended a stay on the
reinstatement order until 17:00 (local time) Monday or until
further orders.
</P>
<P>
Some experts say the dispute, which is expected to be
prolonged, would affect the local foreign exchange market and the
nation's trade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Australian dollar also ended at 84.65 Japanese
yen from 84.95 yen and at 1.1707 Deutsche marks from 1.17 marks.
</P>
