<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Venture to Produce Cheaper Irrigation Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Irrifrance Corp. announced today
that it will set up a joint venture in China to produce cheaper
irrigation equipment to cater to Chinese farmers.
</P>
<P>
At today's close of Agro Expo China '98, an official from the
French company said that he will go to east China's Shandong
Province to negotiate with government officials after the expo.
</P>
<P>
Irrigation technology had become a hot exhibition item on the
expo. Nearly 100 irrigation equipment producers and designers from
domestic and overseas firms attended the four-day exhibition,
making up 20 percent of the participants.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural experts said this indicates that the country --
not only the central government but also firms and farmers -- are
aware of the importance of water-saving irrigation.
</P>
<P>
China, with a per capita water availability of 2,300 cubic
meters, is one of 13 countries with the most serious water
shortage problems in the world.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 80 percent of the country's water supply flows to
farmers, but only 40 percent of the water is efficiently used.
</P>
<P>
To conserve water, the Ministry of Water Resources plans to
raise prices. It also plans to stop approving non-water-saving
agricultural projects this year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers used to flood their grain crops. Water-saving
irrigation measures were only used for fruit and cash crops
in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, new irrigation methods have been used for
field crops. So far, China has set up five model fields using new
methods with each covering more than 660,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
China will be the host of an international irrigation expo next
year, according to the Specialized Sub-Council of Agriculture
under the Chinese Council for Promotion of International Trade,
the organizer of Agro Expo China '98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
