<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Marc Dutroux, the man charged with murdering at least four
little girls in Belgium, escaped from his prison Thursday
afternoon. He was re-captured by the police some 20 kilometers
from his prison. The three-hour escape of the public enemy of
Belgium shook the country. The interior minister and minister of
justice resigned immediately at the demand of the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
-- The American media have accused the French army, which is
traditionally pro-Serb, of helping the Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic of escaping a plan by the NATO force to arrest him in the
summer of 1997. The Washington Post said on Thursday that a French
army officer, Commander Herve Gourmelon, had met Karadzic several
times in 1997 in breaking the rule of the allied force in Bosnia,
which created a gap between the U.S. and French troops.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- France was cut into two in terms of investment by foreigners
in the country last year. Three-fourth of the jobs created by
foreigners in France were on the eastern side of the the
Havre-Lyon-Marseille line, especially in the northeastern part of
the country which is close to the heart of Europe. Unemployment rate
has dropped in Alsace, Champagne-Ardenne, Rhone-Alpes,
Nord-Pas-de-Calais and Provence-Alpes-Cote d'Azur, while the Grand
West region or Languedoc-Rousillon has become a forgotten corner of
investors.
</P>
<P>
-- The French government recognized on Thursday the existence of
"relations" which "could have appeared contestable" between a
French army officer who used to serve in NATO force in Bosnia and
Bosnian Serb leaders accused of war crimes. But it denied that a
plan by American troops to arrest Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic last summer had been tipped off by the French officer,
Herve Gourmelon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
