<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phoenix's Manning Wins NBA Sixth Man Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Danny Manning of the Phoenix Suns
was named the winner of the 1997-98 NBA Sixth Man Award, designed
to honor the league's premier player who served as a reserve in
more games than he started, the NBA Asia said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Manning received 57 out of a possible 116 votes from a panel of
sports writers and broadcasters throughout the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
Kobe Bryant of the Los Angeles Lakers finished second with 31
votes and Seattle's Dale Ellis was third with 21 votes.
</P>
<P>
Seven players received votes, including New York's John Starks
with three, Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse with two, Milwaukee's
Michael Curry with one and Washington's Tracy Murray with one.
</P>
<P>
Manning averaged 13.5 points, 5.6 rebounds, 2.0 assists and
1.01 steals per game while coming off the bench in 59 of the 70
games in which he played this season.
</P>
<P>
The 6-10 forward ranked 12th in the NBA in field-goal
percentage and scored 10 or more points 53 times, 15 or more
points 28 times and 20 or more points nine times. He ranked
second in field-goal percentage, third in rebounding and fourth in
scoring for the Suns.
</P>
<P>
Manning, who scored the 10,000th point of his career on
November 26 against New Jersey, had several standout performances
during the season including 35 points, 10 rebounds and three
assists in a 140-139 quadruple overtime win at Portland on
November 14.
</P>
<P>
Manning scored 18 points in the overtimes to boost his total to
35, the most points he has scored in a game during his four-year
career in Phoenix. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
