<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Offers Chittagong Port Service to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has offered for the
first time Chittagong port service to India, official sources said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Bangladeshi special envoy and Foreign Minister Abdus
Samad Azad made the offer during his meeting with Indian leaders
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He offered the facility of the Chittagong port for the transit
of Indian goods to and from its northeastern areas.
</P>
<P>
He also informed Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee
when he called on him here on April 22 that a deep sea port
adjoining the existing port in Chittagong is being built at a cost
of 400 million U.S. dollars for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that Bangladesh has officially offered
the Chittagong port as a transit route to India.
</P>
<P>
India had been pleading with Bangladesh in the past decade to
grant it the use of this facility for the cheaper and easier flow
of its goods to its northeast.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Vajpayee assured Azad that his government
would abide by all the agreements entered into with Dhaka by
previous Indian governments, including the one on the sharing of
Ganges water. He said his government wants to further strengthen
the already existing friendly ties and have all kinds of
cooperation with Dhaka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
