<HEADLINE> Whole Gale Wreaks Havoc in Jiangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A whole gale and heavy hail hit
two cities in east China's Jiangxi Province late Wednesday evening
and early Thursday morning, killing at least 12 people, injuring
over 1,000 people, and causing heavy property damage.
</P>
<P>
Gale force winds and heavy hail lasting some 30 minutes hit
Pingxiang City at around 18:00 p.m. on Wednesday cutting a 10-15
km wide swath of destruction stretching over 60 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Hailstones as large as 75 mm in diameter covered the ground to
depths of as much as 100 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists report that the area last witnessed heavy
hail on the scale in 1957.
</P>
<P>
Local governments report that some 408 houses collapsed,
with an additional 35,000 houses sustaining heavy damage. The
storm also devastated over 13,300 ha of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Estimates indicate that the storm adversely affected the lives
of over 640,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Gale force winds and heavy hail lasting from 21:00 pm on
Wednesday into the early moring hours on Thursday also hit
nine townships in Fengcheng City.
</P>
<P>
Force 10 winds uprooted a poplar tree with a diameter of some
40 cm, and blew a truck carrying a load of over 30 pigs some 200
meters off the road.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the nine townships indicate that 12 people died in
the catastrophe, with some 1,000 people injured, including 110
people suffering from serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
A total of 22,000 people in 5,800 rural households in the
townships were adversely affected by the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi Governor Shu Shengyou rushed to the disaster-stricken
area early Thursday morning to direct relief efforts, with local
governments immediately organizing rescue teams and dispatching
relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
Local agricultural departments responded by providing rice
seedlings, seeds and chemical fertilizers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
