<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Praises S. Africa's Trade Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade
Organization (WTO) Thursday praised South Africa's overall
progress in liberalizing trade in the past four years, South
African newspapers reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In its first review of the new state's trade policies,
released Thursday after three days of discussions, the WTO said
the country's structural reforms since its 1994 general election
have laid a "credible foundation" for making South African
products more competitive internationally.
</P>
<P>
However, the world trade policing body warned that South
Africa must stop using its tariffs for "selective protection" and
must simplify its arrangements under the Southern African Customs
Union along with its fellow union members - Botswana, Lesotho,
Namibia and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
In spite of reforms, South Africa still maintained a system of
duties that "is frequently changed for selective protection", and
the tariff regime of the country as well as the customs union
also remained complex, the WTO said.
</P>
<P>
A revised structure was essential to conform to WTO
obligations, to attract more foreign investment and to ease new
regional agreements, the Geneva-based body said.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the benefits of government trade reforms on
South Africa's competitiveness are being eroded by rising labor
costs.
</P>
<P>
The competitiveness of South African manufacturers, shielded
by tariffs averaging 16 percent, is being hurt by "upward
pressures on unit labor costs resulting partly from a lack of
skilled labor", the WTO said.
</P>
<P>
South African Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin rejected
the criticism of the country's duty system, saying that the
report, completed last year, did not reflect the current
circumstances correctly.
</P>
<P>
He said most of the barriers to trade had been eliminated or
were not effective, and the remaining ones would be removed in
the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Erwin dealt out some criticism of his own, warning that if the
WTO did not improve the institutional capacity of developing
countries to implement WTO rules, it would contribute to "severe
developmental distortions."
</P>
<P>
Erwin in effect said now that developed countries had grown
rich through protectionism, they were denying it to developing
countries when they needed it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
