<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Fiscal Report Optimistic for First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- First-quarter revenue in
Shanghai, China's largest financial and commercial center, was 8.4
billion yuan, up 14 percent over the same period last year,
according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounts for 21.6 percent of the municipality's
annual budget.
</P>
<P>
Taxes from the industrial and commercial sectors were up 13.4
percent compared with the same period last year, with corporate
income taxes of 1.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's fiscal expenditures in the first quarter also
climbed 16 percent to 6.48 billion yuan, mainly flowing into
infrastructure construction, corporate funding, civil
construction, science and education.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding bank deposits in the city's financial institutions
during the period amounted to 554.8 billion yuan, for a surplus of
111.4 billion yuan to bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, outstanding saving deposits reached 220.4 billion
yuan, up 7.3 billion yuan from the end of last year, with 5.76
billion yuan of urban savings and 1.5 billion yuan from farmers.
</P>
<P>
Financial insiders attributed the healthy fiscal record to a
rational policy toward bank loans.
</P>
<P>
In the securities market, the quarterly turnover was down 24.5
percent to 607.9 billion yuan, with 229.3 billion from stock
transactions, down 28.7 percent compared with the corresponding
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The trading of state bonds totaled 375 billion yuan in the
first three months, representing a drop of 1.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Renminbi is still steady against the U.S. dollar, despite
small fluctuations, as figures indicated in China's Foreign
Exchange Trading Center based in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign exchange transactions through the center topped
15.9 billion U.S. dollars in the first three months with daily
turnovers averaging 265 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Inter-bank foreign exchange trading during the period suggested
a downturn of 448 million yuan in average daily transaction
volume. Total turnover for the first quarter was 26.9 billion
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
