<HEADLINE> 11 Passengers Killed in India's Train Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Eleven passengers were killed
and 12 others injured seriously when 10 rear bogies of a goods
train rammed into a stationary express at the Parli Vaijnath
railway station in Maharashtra State's Beep District, Southwest
India, Friday.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the ballast-carrying bogies of the
Hyderabad-bound goods train got disconnected and rolled back into
the station, hitting the rear of the stationary express at the
platform.
</P>
<P>
The rearmost coach of the express train was badly affected
causing most of the casualties, an official release said.
</P>
<P>
Railway Minister Nitish Kumar and other senior officials rushed
to the spot to oversee relief and rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, seven people were killed and 69 others injured
in two road accidents.
</P>
<P>
In one accident, seven died and eight were injured in a
lorry-jeep collision in Karnataka State's Gulbarga District in
southern India Friday morning. Most of the dead were traveling by
the jeep, police said.
</P>
<P>
In the other, at least 61 people were injured when a West
Bengal tourist bus carrying them turned turtle in Uttar Pradesh.
Two of the injured were reported to be in critical condition.
</P>
