<HEADLINE> No Postponement of Local Elections: Chissano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has said that there is no reason to postpone the local
elections scheduled to be held on June 30.
</P>
<P>
A further delay of the elections "means to postpone the
exercise of the people's rights," the Noticias quoted Chissano as
saying Thursday in Monapo, northern Nampula Province.
</P>
<P>
This is the first response Chissano made to the boycott by the
16 opposition parties led by the Mozambican National Resistance
(RENAMO), the biggest opposition.
</P>
<P>
The local elections were initially set to be held in late
1997. But they were put off till May this year and later, the
date was postponed once again to June 30.
</P>
<P>
It may not be a bad thing for the opposition political parties
to withdraw from the elections in late June, Chissano said,
adding that they can make full preparations for the parliamentary
and presidential elections next year.
</P>
<P>
President Chissano Monday started a six-day working tour of
Nampula Province. Monapo is one of the five places the president
is scheduled to visit.
</P>
<P>
Chissano noted that he hopes the local elections next year
will cover the whole country and autonomy can be practised in all
cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an audience of over 3,000 people in Monapo, the
president castigated some state and public units for corrupt
conducts, particularly in the health care sector.
</P>
<P>
He said his government is trying to improve the service of the
state units. For instance, some police officers are receiving
training so that they can better serve the people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
