<HEADLINE> IOC President to Inspect Sydney Olympic Preparations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Sydney will be scrutinised its
preparations for the 2000 Games by Olympic chief Juan Antonio
Samaranch on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The IOC Executive Board will meet from April 27 to 30 alongside
a high-ranking delegation from the Association of Summer Olympic
International Federations (ASOIF).
</P>
<P>
They will check on Olympic facilities, such as transport,
venues, staffing, technology and accommodation before delivering a
report.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the agenda will be politics, which has dominated
preparations and blew up Thursday when Prime Minister John Howard
refused to have any further dealings with New South Wales Olympics
Minister Michael Knight.
</P>
<P>
Another big issue is drugs in sport and the anti-doping
technology used to combat it.
</P>
<P>
IOC member Kevan Gosper last week virtually ruled out
blood-tests, saying it had yet to be proved that it added to the
accuracy of urine-testing.
</P>
<P>
With more than 80 local and international journalists tracking
his every move, the Barcelona-born Samaranch only gave his press
conference on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It is the 77-year-old IOC president's second visit to the city
since it was chosen to host the Games five years ago. 
</P>
