<HEADLINE> Police Station Opened at HK's New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's latest and most
modern police station was opened at the new Chek Lap Kok Airport
Friday.
</P>
<P>
With sophisticated equipment, the station is expected to
perform the same duties as at the Kai Tak airport, both in
preventing and detecting crime and maintaining public order, but
in a much larger airport.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the opening ceremony of the police station,
Commissioner of Police Hui Ki-on said, "Incorporated within the
station is probably the world's most advanced Police Incident
Command Center, which will be used in the event of a major
incident at the airport."
</P>
<P>
"However, I sincerely hope that this facility is never used in
earnest," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the duties of the officers at the new airport which
is to start operation on July 6, he said uniformed officers will
conduct patrols of the spacious passenger terminal building and
surrounding areas, including the whole of the airport island, and
crime officers investigate criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Security Unit, which has been considerably expanded
compared with the unit at Kai Tak, will also be based at the new
airport. There will also be specially trained dogs to detect
explosives.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the station began in October 1995 and was
completed in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
During a press visit to the new station Thursday, Keith
Braithwaite, regional commander of "New Territories" South, said
that by mid-June, the station will be fully manned by more than
330 officers. Presently there are some 80 police officers.
</P>
<P>
Braithwaite expected that with the opening of the new airport,
baggage theft and shop theft would become common types of
offenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
