<HEADLINE> Retail Sales in Hong Kong Decrease in Early 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The value of total retail sales
in Hong Kong for February this year was an estimated 14.7 billion
HK dollars (1.88 billion U.S. dollars), 18 percent less than a
year earlier, according to provisional figures released here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
After discounting the effect of price changes over the period,
total retail sales decreased by 19 percent in volume, the Census
and Statistics Department figures showed.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the timing of the Chinese Lunar New Year, retail
sales tend to show more volatility in the first two months of a
year. The Lunar New Year fell on late January this year but in
early February last year. It is therefore more significant to
compare the retail sales figures for January and February
combined.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first two months of 1998 together, total retail
sales declined by 14 percent in value or 15 percent in volume over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
On a year-on-year comparison, sales in department stores
recorded the largest drop, by 26 percent in value and 28 percent
in volume in the first two months of the year.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by sales of motor vehicles; clothing and
footwear; jewelry, watches and clocks and valuable gifts; and
miscellaneous consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
Sales of food, alcoholic drinks, tobacco and fuels fell more
moderately in the two months, all within 6 percent in both value
and volume.
</P>
<P>
A government secretariat spokesman commented that the setback
in the retail business in early 1998 was due mainly to the
repercussions of the regional financial turmoil on the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
While tourist spending plunged along with the protracted
weakness in inbound tourism, local consumer spending also
slackened considerably since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
The volume of retail sales is derived from the value of retail
sales after adjusting for price changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KCR Promotes Public Understanding of West Rail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Kowloon-Canton
Railway Corporation (KCR) Friday staged an exhibition at Tsuen Wan
to promote the citizens' understanding of a railway project
linking the northwestern part of the "New Territories" and
Kowloon.
</P>
<P>
The three-day exhibition focuses on the background and major
characteristics of the West Rail project, which is scheduled to
begin at the end of this year. KCR staff will explain details of
the project to the public.
</P>
<P>
The 30.3-kilometer West Rail is designed to stretch from
Yen Chow Street to Tuen Mun, with nine stations along
this section of railway, from which passengers can change to the
Mass Transit Railway and the Airport Railway.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 64 billion HK dollars (8.2 billion U.S.
dollars) and the fund will come from the government, commercial
loans and the KCR itself.
</P>
<P>
The northwestern part of the "New Territories" has enjoyed
rapid growth in the past years. The population in this region is
estimated to grow from the current 800,000 to 1.4 million by 2003,
when the West Rail is completed.
</P>
<P>
The West Rail will further promote economic development in the
area and the construction of the railway will create 100,000 to
120,000 jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Issues Codes of Practice Against Discrimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region published on Friday two codes of
practice to address discrimination in the workplace on the grounds
of race and sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
A Home Affairs Bureau spokesman said the codes, known as the
Codes of Practice Against Discrimination in Employment on the
Grounds of Race and Sexual Orientation, aim to encourage employers
and employees to eliminate discriminatory practices in the
workplace through self-regulation.
</P>
<P>
"The codes seek to promote equal employment opportunities among
people of different races and sexual orientations. They reaffirm
the government's commitment to the elimination of all forms of
discrimination," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The codes recommend that, among other things, employers develop
consistent and objective selection criteria in all aspects of
employment, including recruitment, appraisal, promotion, posting,
training, dismissal and redundancy, terms and conditions of
employment benefits, facilities and services.
</P>
<P>
Employers are also encouraged to issue a clear policy statement
that discrimination, harassment and vilification at work will not
be tolerated under any circumstances and to review the policy from
time to time.
</P>
<P>
Employees, for their part, are urged to acquaint themselves
with the recommendations in the codes, help their employers in
introducing and implementing relevant policies and support friends
or colleagues who have lodged -- or intend to lodge -- complaints
about discrimination.
</P>
<P>
To help drive the message home, the government has published a
new leaflet entitled "Equal Opportunities: Race" and re-designed
the leaflet "Equal Opportunities: Sexual Orientation" in a more
lively format. The leaflets set out the government's position on
equal opportunities in these areas and explain the principles
underlying that position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
