<P>
In this secret ballot, Kiriyenko had won 251 votes in the Duma
with 25 against.
</P>
<P>
He needs 226 votes in the 450-seat Duma irrespective of
how many take part in the ballot.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers rejected Kiriyenko in the first two rounds of votes
over the past two weeks. The Communists in the lower house have
described the 35-year-old Kiriyenko as too young and inexperienced
to solve Russia's massive social and economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin has insisted that Kiriyenko, a
former banker and energy minister, is the right man for the job
and will be able to improve the country's economy. 
</P>
