<HEADLINE> Syrian, Egyptian Presidents Talk on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
held talks Friday with visiting Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on the Mideast peace process, the Syrian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The news agency did not disclose details of the talks in the
Mediterranean resort Latakia, to where Mubarak flew earlier in the
day.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's visit is part of the two countries' efforts to
continue consultation and coordination over issues in the Middle
East, particularly the Israeli offer to carry out a conditional
withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad visited Egypt on April 15 to discuss with Mubarak the
response of Syria and Lebanon to the Israeli offer. Mubarak
expressed Egypt's support for the Syrian and Lebanese position.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is to meet with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu on Tuesday, only days before the proposed London
meetings on reviving the peace process will be held. The subject
was apparently included in the talks between Mubarak and al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to accept the United Nations Security
Council Resolution 425 and to withdraw from south Lebanon provided
security arrangements are worked out with Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon, which agree to coordinate their stances on
key issues, including peace-making with Israel, have rejected
Israel's offer, insisting that the withdrawal should be
unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon with the claimed aim to protect its northern areas
from cross-border attacks by Muslim guerrillas. 
</P>
