<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnapped ICRC Workers Released in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The ten kidnapped aid workers
of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) were
officially released by their captors Friday.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were first moved from their place of captivity to
the ICRC run hospital of Keysaney, about a mile north of the
capital, where they were offered a little medical checkup and
refreshment drinks and food.
</P>
<P>
They were also given telephones to contact their offices and
relatives and a plane has been called for to lift them to
Nairobi. The aid workers who all looked healthy but tired were
extremely happy after nine days of captivity.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi Mohamed, a major faction leader in the capital
Mogadishu, spoke with the ICRC staff at the Keysaney Hospital
immediately after their release and gave his apology on behalf of
the Somalis.
</P>
<P>
"This has been an isolated incident and it is not representing
the Somalis in general," he said, adding "the abduction has been
carried out by irresponsible people."
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi also asked ICRC not be discouraged by what had
happened and continue their noble task in helping the poor and
needy Somalis according to the tradition of the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi told Xinhua that no ransom has been paid to free the
ICRC hostages, but added that traditional channels had been used
to release them.
</P>
<P>
However, sources close to the militiamen and the negotiators
indicate that 60,000 US Dollars had been given to the abductors
last night while another 40,000 US Dollars was given to them
Friday morning. Moreover, this money is reported to have come as
contribution offered by the local Somalis.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi's deputy chairman, Ali Ugas Abdulle and the
Secretary General of the Somali Red Crescent Society, Nur Addeh,
were also present at Keysaney Hospital where an airplane is
expected to take the ICRC staff members to Nairobi in an hour
from the press time.
</P>
<P>
The abduction of the aid workers stood in the way of the
establishment of Mogadishu's administration and all of the
general reconciliation process of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
However, Ali Mahdi Mohamed said Friday after the ICRC hostages
were released that from Friday on they are to restart their
business of establishing an all inclusive administration for
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC staff had been abducted by armed Somalis with four
technicals on 15 April at Issaley Airstrip controlled by Ali
Mahdi. Earlier, the abductors had demanded about one million US
Dollars, but the negotiators had resisted firmly all kinds of
such bizarre ransom demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
