<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Recent Russian Government Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Following is a brief chronology of
Russia's recent government crisis starting from President Boris
Yeltsin sacking of Viktor Chernomyrdin's cabinet in March.
</P>
<P>
March 23
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin dismisses Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and the
entire cabinet, and then names Energy Minister Sergei Kiriyenko,
35, as first deputy prime minister and acting prime minister.
</P>
<P>
March 27
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin nominates Kiriyenko as prime minister, and warns the
State Duma, or the lower house of parliament, that he will
dissolve the legislative chamber and call a new parliamentary
election if it does not approve the nomination.
</P>
<P>
April 2
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin meets parliamentary speakers and allows the 450-seat
Duma to postpone debates to April 10.
</P>
<P>
April 10
</P>
<P>
Duma deputies vote 186-143 to reject Kiriyenko's candidacy in
the first round of balloting. Yeltsin immediately resubmits
Kiriyenko as candidate.
</P>
<P>
April 14
</P>
<P>
Gennady Seleznyov, speaker of Duma, urges co-legislators to
vote for Kiriyenko rather than face an early parliament election.
</P>
<P>
April 17
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko fails the second round of voting at Duma, with 115
votes for and 271 votes against. Again, Yeltsin resubmits
Kiriyenko as candidate.
</P>
<P>
April 18
</P>
<P>
Acting First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov makes it clear
that if the Duma turns down Kiriyenko, Yeltsin will install him as
the prime minister by decree.
</P>
<P>
April 22
</P>
<P>
Russia's Federation Council, or the upper house of parliament,
urges the Duma to vote for the confirmation of Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
April 24
</P>
<P>
Duma approved Kiriyenko as prime minister in the third round of
ballot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
