<HEADLINE> Somali Gunmen Releases Aid Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Somali gunmen unconditionally
released 10 Red Cross workers Friday morning, the regional office
of the International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The workers, who were abducted by nearly 40 armed militiamen
in a small airstrip nearby northern Mogadishu on April 15, will
arrive at Nairobi by air later Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"All the workers are in good health," according to the ICRC office.
</P>
<P>
Among the hostages are a South African pilot, an American, a
French, a Norwegian, a Belgian, two Swiss doctors, a German and a
Somali from the Somali Red Crescent Society.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers are said loyal to a renegade member of northern
Mogadishu's military leader Ali Mahdi's Hawiye clan.
</P>
<P>
Since the abduction happened, the Somali capital saw the
withdrawal of all relief agencies and expatriate staff citing
insecurity. About 45 percent of the city's population is
dependent on relief services. 
</P>
