<HEADLINE> Rumbling over Foreign Labor Heats in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The arrest of a Thai worker
suspected of raping and killing a Jewish girl has set off a
rumbling of disquiet in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs has been suggested by
kibbutz (collective farm) residents that regulations be amended to
impose a limit to the number of foreign workers in the country and
closer supervision on them, according to The Jerusalem Post Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police announced early this week that DNA tests
performed on the 29-year-old Thai worker Korbua Sumbat supported
their suspicion that he has raped and murdered a 23-year-old girl
from the Naan Kibbutz in northern Israel on April 10.
</P>
<P>
Sumbat, who was remanded by a court on Wednesday for another 12
days, came to Naan two months ago. He worked in avocado fields and
citrus orchards.
</P>
<P>
After Sumbat's arrest, Israeli Labor and Social Affairs
Minister Eli Ishai said that foreign workers are having a "deadly
effect" on the Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Mizrahi, head of the kibbutz communities, said concern
has been raised within local residents about the safety and
welfare due to inflow of foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
"I have nothing against the workers themselves, but they are
cooped up in one small village with no outlet for their natural
needs and desires," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They are very nice individually, but one of their tendency is
to drink and sometimes get drunk. If this should happen, they are
no longer in control of themselves and this is dangerous," he
added.
</P>
<P>
There are about 200,000 foreign workers in Israel, most of
them came from Romania, Thailand and the Philippines. In some
villages, foreign workers account for about 10 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
Foreign workers have become the backbone of the labor force in
Israel's agriculture in the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
