<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Former Philippine Movie Star Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The May 11 presidential elections
in the Philippines may virtually turn into a one-man show of
ex-movie star turned Vice President Joseph Estrada who remains a
clear favorite of the electorate in two opinion polls conducted
this month.
</P>
<P>
In the April 8-19 poll by the Social Weather Station (SWS), the
country's most trusted pollster, Estrada of the opposition LAMMP
(Filipino acronym for the Fight of Patriotic Filipino Masses
Party) gained a 30-percent support rating, more than double that
of his closest rivals.
</P>
<P>
Poll results issued Thursday also showed that if the election
held today, none of the other 10 candidates could pose a threat to
Estrada, who has topped all the three previous monthly SWS surveys
with a hefty 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
The poll found a virtual three-way tie among former Manila
mayor Alfredo Lim, businessman Emilio Osmena, with 13 percent
each, and Speaker of the House of Representatives Jose de Venecia
with 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's wide lead was underlined by another poll survey
conducted by the independent Philippine Survey and Research
Center. The poll gave Estrada a whopping 34 percent approval,
against 16 percent for his nearest rival Senator Raul Rocco of the
Democratic Action Party.
</P>
<P>
The surging popularity of Estrada in the final stage of the
90-day campaign period was a surprise to many poll pundits who
have predicted an effective three-cornered fight among Estrada,
Lim and De Venecia.
</P>
<P>
It had been expected that De Venecia's rating could continue to
rise given the strong support of President Fidel Ramos and the
ruling Lakas-NUCD Party's powerful political machine.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia, who had been among the tail-enders in many previous
polls, managed to surge to the second place in the March SWS poll
with 14 percent in a tie with Lim, who was backed by former
president Corazon Aquino.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the surveys indicated both Lim and De
Venecia have reached a plateau while the highly popular Estrada
continues to gain strength from the middle-lower classes of the
voters despite repeated mudslingings from his rivals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Former Philippine Movie Star Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Estrada, who made a household name in the 1960s for playing
Robin Hood heroes fighting for the poor, has been a repeated
target of mudslingings and black propaganda from his rivals since
January.
</P>
<P>
The ex-movie star, who turned 61 last week, has long been
accused by his critics of having a series of "sins," which include
heavy drinking, womanizing and gambling.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the influential Roman Catholic Church have also
suggested that the portly and mustache ex-movie star is not
morally fit to govern.
</P>
<P>
Estrada admitted having adulterous affairs, but said those were
"sins" of the past when he was a movie star. He denied having
drinking and gambling problems.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, a college dropout, is also disliked by big business
groups who question his grasp of economic issues especially at a
time when the country's economy has slowed down in the wake of an
Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Estrada himself admitted he is an ignoramus in economics. He
said if elected, he will leave economic affairs to his running
mate Senator Angara Edgardo, a lawyer and a recognized economist.
</P>
<P>
But Estrada said it is unnecessary for the business community
to be afraid of an economic slump under an Erap (his nickname)
presidency since "the economy has already slowed down due to the
Asian financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
To ease the resistance from the business circle and foreign
investors, Estrada, who runs on a populist pro-poor platform,
promised to continue Ramos' economic reforms which have turned the
country into "an emerging tiger."
</P>
<P>
There were even more serious charges against him in the past
two months, which include his secret plot to murder Ramos and his
involvement in a pyramid scam.
</P>
<P>
But it seemed that all these attacks made no dent on Erap's
high popularity among the middle-lower classes who have seen him
as their hero and savior.
</P>
<P>
Columnist Emil Jurado said: "Instead of the demolition job on
Erap eroding his popularity among the masa (Filipino form for
mass), it has endeared him more to them."
</P>
<P>
"It's the typical Filipino psyche which tends to side with the
underdog. And since Erap is their idol, he has become both their
hero and the underdog," he explained.
</P>
<P>
"The Erap phenomenon goes beyond the fact that Erap, the 'hero'
whom the masses identify with, has gained more sympathy with all
his detractors and political enemies throwing everything in his
direction."
</P>
<P>
The latest poll results were hailed by Erap's camp, which
claimed that the May 11 presidential poll was already in Estrada's
bag.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos, who won the 1992 elections with a narrow margin as
indicated by most pre-election SWS polls, laughed off the claim.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who is barred by the constitution from seeking
re-election, said that Estrada's emergence as consistent top
notcher in the presidential surveys did not guarantee he would
emerge victorious.
</P>
<P>
Lakas national campaign manager Cesar Sarino also debunked the
surveys, saying the ruling party's strong political machine will
finally lead De Venecia to victory in the May 11 ballot.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts, however, predicts that Erap will continue to be
a front runner till the May 11 showdown as a result of the
bandwagon effect caused by the poll surveys.
</P>
<P>
"From hereon, we will see some mayors, governors and
congressmen and leaders of other political parties gravitating
towards him," said Jurado. "It has always been so since no
politician wants to be identified with the loser."
</P>
<P>
Likewise, a regrouping of campaign financiers is also expected.
Some campaign contributors is seen to give up low-ranking
candidates and swing their support to Estrada for better
investment, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Alarmed by the soaring popularity of Estrada, Manila Archbishop
Jaime Cardinal Sin, the country's leading prelate, urged Thursday
Estrada's trailers to make a sacrifice by merging forces to stop
the controversial Estrada from winning.
</P>
<P>
"The most probable winner could be the most probably disastrous
for the country," said the influential Catholic Church leader in a
pastoral statement. But he himself admitted earlier that Estrada
is unbeatable. "If there is no cheating, he is going to win," Sin
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
