<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippines Retrieves Part of Marcos' Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was reported that the rest 240 million dollars would soon be
returned to the Philippines. But how to divide or use the money
has aroused harsh controversies.
</P>
<P>
The Marcos family said that according to a secret deal it
signed with the Fidel Ramos administration, the government had 75
percent of the money and the family had 25 percent. The government
denied the deal while the human rights victims of the Marcos
regime said they should be given top priority to have about 100
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Right at this time, Imelda, who was on parole and campaigning
to run for the presidency in the coming May 11 elections, said the
family had at least 800 million dollars more and she would scatter
the wealth to the poor if she wins the presidency.
</P>
<P>
"There is more Marcos wealth that this government is not yet
aware of, but for the time being I can admit that there is only
800 million dollars kept in various international banks, but I can
not reveal them," she said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Imelda has publicly admitted her
family had more than what the government has discovered. Although
analysts said Imelda's statement has political colors, the
government decided to widen the search for Marcos' wealth.
</P>
<P>
But How much money did the Marcos family have? Where did they
put it? When can the government retrieve all the money? Nobody can
answer these questions. Analysts believed that it is no easy job
for the Philippine government to recover the Marcos wealth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
