<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippines Retrieves Part of Marcos' Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- After 12 years of legal battles,
the Philippines recently recovered for the first time about 300
million U.S. dollars of the late President Ferdinand Marcos'
wealth.
</P>
<P>
Magtanggol Gunigundo, Chairman of the Presidential Commission
on Good Government, said the money has been transferred to the
country from Swiss banks and deposited on an escrow account of the
Philippine National Bank.
</P>
<P>
The money was part of the 540 million dollars the Swiss Supreme
Court ordered to be returned to the country. The Philippine
government said the wealth was "looted" from state treasury by
Marcos during his 20 years' ruling of the country.
</P>
<P>
Marcos was toppled in 1986 in a popular revolt and died in
Hawaii, the United States three years later. After he fled the
country, the then new president, Corazon Aquino, immediately began
the work to retrieve his ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
However, because of political turmoils, natural disasters and
the "self defense" of the Marcos family, the Aquino administration
made little progress in recovering the wealth.
</P>
<P>
Although the Swiss Supreme Court ruled twice during the past
few years that the money should be transferred to the Philippines,
it was until the end of last year that Manila saw the hope of
solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the court ruled again that two Swiss banks
should return to the Philippines 100 million dollars of Marcos'
wealth which has grown to 540 million dollars due to accrued
interest.
</P>
<P>
The court extended the amount to the whole 540 million dollars
in January this year, but the prerequisite was that Imelda, the
former First Lady and inheritor of the Marcos wealth, must be
proven guilty in a fair and final trial.
</P>
<P>
During the past 12 years, Gunigundo's commission and victims
under the Marcos regime lodged at least 36 charges against Imelda.
But due to lack of evidence, all the charges except one had been
dismissed by the courts.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, the third division of the Philippine
Supreme Court announced that it upheld a local court's ruling in
1993 that sentenced Imelda to 9 to 12 years in imprisonment for a
land deal, in which she allegedly profiteered by renting a piece
of government land at very low prices and leasing it out at high
prices.
</P>
<P>
Imelda appealed to the court, but was rejected. Her supporters
in Panama and Liechtenstein appealed to the Swiss court to repeal
the ruling, but also failed. So all blocks to the transfer of the
wealth had been cleared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
