<HEADLINE> China Bank Increases Support for Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of China (BOC), the
country's major foreign exchange bank, will increase its loans to
Chinese enterprises that conduct foreign trade on their own, a
bank official said.
</P>
<P>
The bank's lending to such enterprises has been budgeted at 10
billion yuan, up two billion yuan from last year, a bank official
said, adding that financial support for specialized foreign trade
companies will also increase.
</P>
<P>
The move is intended to boost China's foreign trade and thereby
to ensure the successful realization of the nation's eight percent
economic growth plan this year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
China's export growth has slowed down partly due to the
persisting Asian financial crisis, which has resulted in massive
currency devaluations in Thailand, the Philippines, Malaysia, the
Republic of Korea, among other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Figures of the State Statistics Bureau released today indicate
that China's exports totaled 40.2 billion US dollars in the first
three months of this year, up 13.2 percent from the same period of
last year. The growth rate is significantly down from the 20.9
percent rise for the whole of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Figures also show that China's first quarter exports to other
Asian countries and regions was up merely 4.8 percent, with
exports to ASEAN member countries down 17.6 percent. Exports to
Japan edged down 1.7 percent while those to the Republic of Korea
dropped by 22.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The BOC official said that bank loans will be used to help
Chinese enterprises to tap the international market.
</P>
<P>
BOC had extended foreign trade-related loans to more than
3,000 enterprises by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
China has planned its foreign trade volume this year at 345
billion US dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
