<HEADLINE> Positive Changes Seen in UNCHR Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- More dialogue and cooperation and
less confrontation are the positive changes at the 54th session of
the United Nations Commission on Human Rights (UNCHR), said head
of the Chinese delegation Wu Jianmin here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, he said, among them the most striking is
that no anti-China resolution by the U.S. and its Western partners
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a draft by the U.S. aimed at renewing the resolution
to probe Cuba's human rights situation was also turned down, he
said.
</P>
<P>
This demonstrates that to use human rights to provoke
confrontation and interfere in others' internal affairs has become
more and more unpopular.
</P>
<P>
However, the session was not totally free of confrontation
still adopting 13 country-by-country resolutions against the
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
"Confrontation is a dead end," Wu stressed, and the right way
to promote and protect human rights is dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Under continuous calls for years by the developing countries,
Wu said, the current session has given relatively more emphasis to
the economic, social and cultural rights as compared to the
previous ones.
</P>
<P>
Wu hoped that the spirit shown this time will be observed and
pledged that the Chinese delegation is willing to do its best to
put an end to the confrontation existing in the commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
