<HEADLINE> Air Quality Report for China's Major Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Xinhua will release weekly air
quality reports on major Chinese cities from the China Environment
Monitoring Center, starting today.
</P>
<P>
It gives the air quality atmospheric pollution index (API) of
sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen oxide (NOX), and total suspended
particles (TSP).
</P>
<P>
The air quality has five levels according to the State
Environmental Protection Administration. An API from 0 to 50 is
level I, meaning excellent air quality; 51 to 100 is level II, or
good quality; 101 to 200 is level III, or slight pollution; 201 to
300 is level IV, or medium pollution; and above 300 is level V, or
heavy pollution.
</P>
<P>
This week's report says that, from April 17 to 23, some cities
were seriously polluted by dust from northwestern dust storms.
</P>
<P>
The API of Nanjing, Hangzhou, and Beijing was above 300 and the
biggest problem was TSP.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, Hefei, Kunming, Nanning, Nanchang, Dalian, Zhuhai,
and Xiamen had good air quality, with an API level 2. Beihai in
the south had excellent air quality, with an API of 47.
</P>
<P>
Following is the air quality report from April 17 to 23:
</P>
<P>
