<HEADLINE> Platini Forecasts Potential Winners in World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Michel Platini, president of French
1998 World Cup Organizing Committee, said Brazil is the best squad
technically that boast of players with skills.
</P>
<P>
However, the best technical team was not a sure bet to win the
32-member World Cup as rivals with potentials can quene up for a
long line, said the former European top scorer.
</P>
<P>
While Brazil has a better chance of winning the title, Germany,
Italy and England are also capable of making miracles, and France,
Spain, Yugoslavia and even Nigeria have the hope of winning the
World Cup, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the previous 15 World Cups, the titles were swept by six
national teams in which only Uruguay is surely without any slim
hope of taking the title in France, said Platini.
</P>
<P>
Despite its last title dated back to 32 years ago, England can
still cherish its hope, while Germany has been consistent as a
strong candidate in the World Cup history, he said.
</P>
<P>
To forecast the prospect for France, Platini said "France can
win" the World Cup on its home turf.
</P>
<P>
Platini further said that the most favored player, in the fans'
view, usually fails to become a super star in the soccer's biggest
gala and that has been justified in the 68-year history of the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Many talent footballers did not take the limelight of the World
Cup, "and even myself was usually plagued into injuries prior to
the final stages, including the 1982 finals," said Platini. 
</P>
</TEXT>
