<HEADLINE> Korda's No.1 Dream Fails in Monte Carlo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Petr Korda of Czech Republic failed
on his fourth attempt in ten weeks to take over the world number
one ranking as he failed to enter the semifinals of the Monte
Carlo Open in Monaco on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands, former Wimbledon champion,
snapped Korda's dream with a 4-6, 7-6 (7/1), 6-1 quarter-final
victory in the 2.2 million U.S. dollars clay court tournament.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old Korda previously had chances to grab the top
spot over the past two months at Antwerp in February and Indian
Wells and Lipton in the United States last month.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the Czech failed every time to win the match he needed to
take over the number one place.
</P>
<P>
Korda's defeat means that Pete Sampras, trounced 6-1, 6-1 on
Thursday by Frenchman Fabrice Santoro in the third round, will get
back the top spot when the next rankings are released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Boris Becker, a three-time finalist who has never won a clay
court title, was aiming for the semifinals with a match against
12th seed Spaniard Alberto Berasategui while Frenchman Cedric
Pioline and Santoro were playing in another quarterfinal. 
