<HEADLINE> 24th FAO Regional Conference Ends in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The five-day 24th Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) Regional Conference for Asia and
the Pacific wound up here Friday with adoption of a report calling
for concerted efforts by all countries in the region to implement
the World Food Summit Plan of Action.
</P>
<P>
The report also called on countries in the region to be
resolute in sustaining resource allocations for agriculture and
food security in face of the constraints that the recent economic
crisis had imposed on some countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The conference expressed concern over the EI Nino phenomenon
and other natural disasters, and requested the FAO to support
these countries in their preparedness to deal with natural
disasters and assist them by strengthening national and regional
early warning systems within the framework of the Global
Information and Early Warning System.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the fact that about 85 percent of the world's
fishers live in Asia and the Pacific which contribute more than
half of the world's fishery production, the conference agreed that
urgent action is needed to promote fisheries and to accelerate
development of sustainable aquaculture.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, Jacques Diouf, Director-General of the FAO,
called for regional and sub-regional cooperation in drawing up
effective framework in support of the sustainable development of
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The conference agreed that the next FAO Regional Conference for
Asia and the Pacific will be held in Tokyo, Japan, in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which began on Monday with a three-day senior
officials meeting and a two-day ministerial meeting, is the first
regional gathering of agricultural ministers since the 1996 World
Food Summit held in Rome, Italy.
</P>
<P>
Attending the conference were about 150 representatives from
26 FAO member countries in Asia and the Pacific, U.N. agencies
and non-governmental organizations. A nine-member Chinese
delegation led by Vice Minister of Agriculture Wan Baorui also
attended the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Members Urged to Cooperate in Nuclear Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Friday called on member states to enhance cooperation
in application of nuclear science and technology for African
development.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Daniel Antonio, acting secretary general
of OAU at the opening session of the second OAU seminar on
nuclear science and technology at the OAU secretariat here.
</P>
<P>
Antonio said the African regional cooperative agreement for
research, development and training related to nuclear science and
technology (AFRA) is one of the very successful models in
embodying such cooperation among African countries.
</P>
<P>
Now, he pointed out that one of the main goals and objectives
of the seminar is to increase awareness and to inform OAU member
states who are not members of the agency, about the importance of
the issues of radiation safety and waste management at their
respective countries.
</P>
<P>
He announced that the OAU has allocated a fund in its budget
for 1998/99, for convening the third seminar and asked any
interested member states, who wishes to host the forthcoming
seminar, to contact the secretariat in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, Qian Jihui, deputy director general of the
International Atomic Energy Agency said since April 1990, when
the AFRA entered into force, 23 African countries have become
members and there are now 13 cooperative projects dealing with
several areas that are of priority.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the partners in development, which include
the agency and the OAU, have faith in AFRA's ability to guide
the efforts of this region to build upon the existing
capabilities in nuclear science and technology as well as taking
on the challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
On the two main issues of the seminar, radiation safety and
waste management, Qian said the agency welcomes the initiative
taken by the secretariat of the OAU to address these issues,
adding that "We are also fully supportive of the proposed action
plan which aims at making use of the influence of the OAU and of
AFRA to accelerate the promulgation and enforcement of national
legislation on radiation protection and to improve the technical
infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar elected Egypt and the Democratic Republic
of Congo as chairman and vice-chairman respectively.
</P>
<P>
The first seminar was held at Kampala, Uganda in April, 1990
on the theme of "Africa's role in nuclear science for peace and
development." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Helping China Get Funds For Water Resources Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government is
working with China's Water Resources Ministry to find ways to
improve its ways of getting foreign investment for water resources
and hydro-electric power projects.
</P>
<P>
The Canada International Development Agency (CIDA) has offered
the ministry 200,000 Canadian dollars and sent some specialists to
help study China's current policy on foreign investment in the
sector, according to Yuan Tanlin, of the Ministry's Foreign
Investment Management Office.
</P>
<P>
Yuan told Xinhua today that China's foreign investment policies
in water resources have failed to catch up with market changes,
one reason that overseas investors are not interested in water
resources development in China.
</P>
<P>
China had 480 million US dollars worth of foreign investment in
water resources development during the 1992-1996 period, only
about 0.3 percent of China's total foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Yuan said China needs to take Canadian know-how into serious
consideration.
</P>
<P>
CIDA uses Canada China Power Inc. (CCPI), which consists of
three of Canada's foremost engineering consulting firms in the
power sector, to do consulting. It has been involved in most of
the major water resources and hydroelectric projects in China that
have required foreign technical assistance, like the Three Gorges,
Xiaolangdi, and Wanjiazhai projects
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
