<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF-imposed Interest Rates on South Korea Need to Be Lowered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The high interest rates imposed by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on South Korea need to be
lowered to help improve the nation's debt repayment capability,
Minister for Finance and Economy Lee Kyu-sung said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The negative consequences of the current IMF-imposed tight
monetary policy are becoming more and more apparent, Lee told the
"Meet the New Leadership" conference here.
</P>
<P>
Because of increasing bankruptcies in South Korea, "a reduction
of the interest rates is urgent and should be implemented no later
than May," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since last December, every month has seen some 3,000 South
Korean firms went belly up, according to the Bank of Korea.
</P>
<P>
South Korea signed an agreement with the IMF last December for
a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars after it was gripped by a
financial crisis triggered by corporate collapses and bad loans of
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that recent stability of the South Korean
currency, won, together with improvements in the current account,
suggest that the domestic interest rate could be lowered without
eroding foreign investor confidence, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Assuming that the IMF will agree to lowering the rates, the
South Korean government could deal with corporate and financial
reforms more decisively and effectively," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the ruin of the South Korean corporate sector
can only undermine the country's debt payment capability.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference started here Thursday and was attended
by some 350 delegates from multinational companies across the
world. At the conference, South Korean President Kim Dae-Jung has
called for more foreign investment to his country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
