<HEADLINE> Germany Pledges 34,800 Tons of Food Aid to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The government of the
Federal Republic of Germany has pledged up to 34,800 metric tons
of food aid to Ethiopia during 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Herald, a government newspaper, Friday quoted an
announcement by the German embassy here as saying that 23,300
metric tons of the total package will be delivered in chronically
food deficit areas in Tigrai and Amhara regions and the remaining
11,500 metric tons is to be channeled through the World Food
Program for the "food for work project" under the Ministry of
Agriculture as well as a refugee program.
</P>
<P>
According to the embassy, this year's pledge represents an
increase of nearly 9,000 metric tons over that of 1997 and is a
clear response of the German government to the emergency needs of
Ethiopia in 1998, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Disaster Prevention and Preparedness Commission of
Ethiopia has appealed to international donor community for
572,835 metric tons of food aid for 1998, saying that over 4.2
million people in the country need relief food in 1998. 
</P>
