<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Making Stricter Land Use Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature is
drafting "the world's strictest law" on land use and farmland
protection, an amendment to the Land-Use Law, which is scheduled
for deliberation by the Second Session of the National People's
Congress Standing Committee on April 26.
</P>
<P>
It states that land-use offices need to make maintaining the
country's farmland as their top priority, the director of the
Policy and Law Department of the new Land and Natural Resources
Ministry, Gan Zangchun, who was in charge of the drafting, said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The amendment needs to see to it that farmland increases and
land for construction is controlled, and urban planning should not
come in conflict with the nation's land use plan, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has its first law on land use since 1986, but legal
scholars say that the law is somewhat unsuitable for a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
The draft includes measures for protecting farmland, the
compensation system for farmland, and penalties for violations.
</P>
<P>
The ministry says that China has 130 million hectares of
farmland, an average of 0.1 hectare for each person. The United
Nations Food and Agriculture Organization has set a minimum of per
capita farmland of 0.05 hectare.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural restructuring and disasters in recent years have
destroyed more than 4.7 million hectares of farmland, and
non-agricultural construction claimed another 1.97 million
hectares, so China is in bad need of better land use management.
</P>
<P>
After deliberation by the NPC Standing Committee, the draft
might be shown to the public for suggestion, sources say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
