<HEADLINE> Blatter Admits Errors in World Cup Tickets Allocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- FIFA General Secretary Sepp
Blatter on Friday acknowledged errors in the World Cup ticketing
system and pledged for a different version in future.
</P>
<P>
"It (the ticketing system) has worked well for three World
Cups...and now the same system did not work well. We cannot repeat
the error so we will change in the future," Blatter said in the
BBC television.
</P>
<P>
Several European countries, with Britain the most vociferous,
protested that they have not been allocated sufficient tickets and
have been angered by France receiving the lion's share.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Britain asked France to improve the efficiency of
a telephone ticket hotline which has frustrated fans across Europe
for two days, with million of calls being made to try to obtain
tickets.
</P>
<P>
Blatter, who is also seeking the presidency of FIFA, said the
new system in future would be adjusted on a one-by-one basis,
especially when many neighbouring countries were taking part in
the competition.
</P>
<P>
"We have repeated the same system since I am working in
FIFA. It worked well for Mexico, for Italy -- there were empty
seats in Italy -- and for the U.S. and now the same system did not
work so well here," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
