<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Is Hope for Afghan Peace Reborn? (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The war-weary Afghans' hope for
peace seems to be rekindled as Afghanistan's warring factions are
going to enter into negotiations for an early end to the
protracted conflict ravaging their homeland.
</P>
<P>
Five delegates from the Afghan Islamic Taliban militia and nine
from the rival Northern Alliance, who together make up a Joint
Steering Committee, are hopefully to meet here on Saturday under
the auspices of the United Nations and the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Taliban and the Northern Alliance will be
the first face-to-face encounter between the two rivals in more
than a year. The representatives of the two sides had met thrice
here last year but failed to make any progress.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan has over the last one year been practically divided
into two parts, three fourths under the Taliban and the rest under
the Northern Alliance, with each side trying to upset the
situation through use of armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming talks between the mainly ethnic-Pushtoon
militia, and the alliance led by ethnic-Uzbek, Tajik and Hazara
warlords, was made possible after recent hectic diplomatic efforts
made by the U.N., the OIC, Pakistan and other countries who have
strong influence in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Though the two sides have some differences over the agenda of
the talks, Taliban and the alliance have asserted that they would
focus on the formation of Ulema (religious scholar) Commission,
besides other issues like ceasefire and exchange of prisoners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Is Hope for Afghan Peace Reborn? (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Joint Steering Committee, proposed by Taliban, is yet
another attempt to iron out their differences on the composition
of the Ulema Commission which, if and when formed, will bear the
responsibility for deciding the political set-up in Kabul, the
Afghan capital.
</P>
<P>
The hard-line Taliban had rejected the first Ulema list of the
Northern Alliance last month, claiming that the alliance had
proposed disqualified religious scholars.
</P>
<P>
Head of the U.N. Afghan Mission in Islamabad N. Gobi has said
that the modalities of this new round of talks will be decided on
Friday by the representatives of both sides themselves while the
duration "depends on how the process moves forward."
</P>
<P>
Gobi is to jointly preside over Saturday's intra-Afghan meeting
with Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, OIC Assistant Secretary General, who
just arrived here Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Terming the meeting as an important development for peace and
stability in Afghanistan, Bakar said Friday upon his arrival at
the Islamabad airport that the Muslim world is expecting a
positive outcome of the long-waited talks among the Afghan warring
factions.
</P>
<P>
"It is a good omen that the Afghan leaders have realized the
need of an early end of the prevailing rift among their ranks," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Iftikhar Murshed, Pakistan's special envoy on Afghanistan, also
said Friday that he is hopeful that the process of the
intra-Afghan talks will move forward settling the contentious
issues among the warring factions.
</P>
<P>
However, some political observers here sounded a note of
caution against high expectations from the forthcoming Joint
Steering Committee meeting, which is being held at an extremely
low level.
</P>
<P>
The observers said given the rigid and inflexible position of
the Afghan warlords, it would be unrealistic to expect immediate
results from the proposed peace talks.
</P>
<P>
And the experiences of the last few years have convincingly
demonstrated the futility of the intra-Afghan dialogue without
achieving an agreement among the countries who are supporting
different Afghan warring factions, they said.
</P>
<P>
Nobody is expecting a quick fix in the Afghan peace process,
especially at a time when the traditional Afghan fighting season
is about to begin, the observers said, adding that the real fear
is that both Taliban and the Northern Alliance are just buying
time from the international community to prepare for a summer
offensive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
