<HEADLINE> S.Korean, U.S. Experts Research Policy on DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Experts from South Korea and the
United States on Friday started a two-day workshop here for new
strategies on the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Draft policies will be made and presented to Seoul and
Washington after a review on the DPRK's situation.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is co-sponsored by the Seoul Forum and the New
York-based U.S. Council on Foreign Relations after the
inter-Korean talks in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The talks last week failed to produce specific results due to
South Korea's persistence to link its fertilizer aid to the DPRK
with other political issues, a stance strongly opposed by
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Workshop sponsors have been conducting a joint research program
on the Korean issues, named the "Korea Project", since last
November.
</P>
<P>
Proposals to be made by the workshop are expected to have a
significant impact on the Clinton Administration's policies on the
Korean Peninsula, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
Among the more than 30 researchers at the workshop are Morton
Abramowitz, former U.S. assistant secretary of state, James Laney,
former U.S. ambassador in Seoul, Richard Allen, former
U.S. national security adviser, and former South Korean Foreign
Minister Han Sung-joo. 
</P>
