<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Making Cutting Of Rare Trees And Their Export Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature is
drafting an amendment to the Forestry Law to be submitted to the
Second Session of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress on April 26 on cutting rare trees and exporting them.
</P>
<P>
The revised law provides criminal penalties for illegal
deforestation or the destruction of rare plants, based on the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild
Flora and Fauna.
</P>
<P>
China has been actively involved in the convention activities
and has taken steps to protect wildlife resources since it joined
the group in 1981. Endangered tree exports have to be approved by
the Chinese convention authorities.
</P>
<P>
The revised Criminal Law, which was adopted last year, states
that people with serious violations of the Forestry Law can be
jailed for three to seven years.
</P>
<P>
China has over 10,000 unique species of wild plants, like the
ginkgo and metasequoia, but experts say that many rare plants are
disappearing as the population grows.
</P>
<P>
China adopted its first regulation on protecting wild animals
and plants in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980424.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
