<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Ministers Arrive for SAARC Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from India, Nepal and Sri
Lanka arrived here Friday to attend the first SAARC information
ministers' meeting, scheduled to start here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Upon her arrival at the airport, Indian Minister for
Information and Broadcasting Sushma Swaraj said the two-day
meeting would help cement regional ties with enhanced cultural
exchanges among the South Asian countries, the national news
agency BSS reported.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see good ties among the SAARC countries and
people," and "information ministers are the appropriate channel to
perform such tasks," she said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the common cultural heritage in the region, Sri
Lankan Minister for Post, Telecommunications and Media Mangala
Samaraweera told reporters that the South Asian people have many
common grounds to enhance the existing ties and bonds, the BSS
reported.
</P>
<P>
Nepalese Minister for Communications Mahant Thakur expressed
the hope that the forthcoming SAARC information ministers' meeting
would enhance the people-to-people communications in the field of
media.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Information Minister Mushahid Hussain and SAARC
Secretary General Naeem U Hasan arrived here Thursday for the
conference, to be inaugurated by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC, established in December 1985, groups Bangladesh,
Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
